<HEADLINE> Concerted Efforts Needed Against Crime: Ugandan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Vice President
Specioza Hazibwe Monday urged African countries to strengthen
cooperation and collaboration in prevention of crimes and
treatment of offenders.
</P>
<P>
She made the call here when opening the African Regional
Preparatory Meeting for the Tenth United Nations Congress on the
Prevention of Crime and the Treatment of Offenders.
</P>
<P>
"As we join the rest of the world in globalization, no tribe
or society can claim ownership to a culture. We should
internalize globalization in the real sense and should have the
global way of dealing with crimes," the senior Ugandan official
said at the three-day conference.
</P>
<P>
She urged participants at the meeting to pay special attention
to crimes in African countries which are in the process of
development.
</P>
<P>
"African leaders have a commitment against crimes which are
complicated by worsening poverty, internal strife and rapid
population growth," she said.
</P>
<P>
All African countries should strengthen technical cooperation
and information exchange in this field, she added.
</P>
<P>
Hazibwe also asserted that it is very important that common
people should participate in the campaign against crimes.
</P>
<P>
This preparatory meeting was attended by more than 100
delegates from African countries.
</P>
<P>
The Tenth U.N. Congress on Prevention of Crime and Treatment
of Offenders is scheduled to open in Geneva in 2000 and the last
one opened in Cairo, Egypt, in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
