<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Withdraws More Troops From Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Monday
withdrew more troops from Lesotho after a September military
intervention in the neighboring kingdom, a senior officer said in
Maseru, the capital of Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
About 200 South African National Defense Force (SANDF) troops
left Maseru in the morning for Bleomfontein, a central city about
150 km west from Lesotho border, said Colonel Hannes van der
Merwe, commander of the combined South African and Botswana
troops.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, 30 South African military engineers would return
to Pretoria, and 150 troops would go back to Grahamstown, a city
between Port Elizabeth and East London.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 650 South African military men, who are operating
in the northern districts of Lesotho, would returned home during
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
In September, a nationwide turmoil erupted in Lesotho when
opposition parties in the country claimed the May 23 election was
rigged in favor of the ruling Lesotho Congress of Democracy.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of Lesotho Prime Minister Pakalitha
Mosisili, South Africa and Botswana sent their troops, in the
name of the South African Development Community (SADC), to
Lesotho to help quell riots.
</P>
<P>
The maximum number of troops that South Africa sent into
Lesotho were about 3500.
</P>
<P>
About 650 SANDF and 500 Botswana Defense Force troops who
constituted the fighting element of the SADC task force, would
remain in Lesotho to ensure that the security situation in the
country returned to normal, SANDF said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
