<HEADLINE> Sema Win Race for Olympic Technology Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee has awarded one of world sport's largest information
technology deals to the Anglo-French Sema Group, according to a
press release from Lausanne on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sema, one of Britain's top 100 companies won the IT contract
for the 2004 and 2008 Summer Olympics and the Winter Games in
2002 and 2006.
</P>
<P>
The firm will step into the shoes of International Business
Machines Corp (IBM) which has decided to end its 40-year
association with the Olympics after the next Games in Sydney in
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Sema has signed a partnership agreement with IOC whereby it
will join a group of leading Olympic sponsors.
</P>
<P>
As technology systems integrator, it will supervise IT
suppliers and be responsible for diffusion of data to world press
agencies and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
It will also oversee the running of information systems for
matters such as accreditation, accommodation and transport.
</P>
<P>
The cost of supplying information technology for the 2002 and
2004 Games, in Salt Lake City and Athens respectively, is
estimated at around 300 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The venues for the Winter Games in 2006 and the Summer Games
in 2008 have yet to be decided. 
</P>
</TEXT>
