<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Says Not to Soften Stand on Anti-dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government said
Monday that it would not soften its stand towards Western
countries on anti-dumping laws.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions in Rajya Sabha, the Upper House of Indian
Parliament, Commerce Minister Ramakrishna Hedge said he denied the
suggestions that India was soft either in terms of law or action
towards Western countries in dealing with anti-dumping rules.
</P>
<P>
Hedge said goods imported from countries including the United
States, China, Japan, Korea and Canada were subjected to
anti-dumping laws in India.
</P>
<P>
The minister denied the reports that the newly created
directorate of anti-dumping was hesitant to take action against
big countries.
</P>
<P>
On economic sanctions imposed by some countries and
international organizations following India's nuclear tests last
May, Hedge said the impact so far had been minimal.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, any precise quantification of the impact of
the sanctions might be difficult and the government was closely
monitoring the likely impact of the restrictive economic measures.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
