<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder at Odds with Simitis over EU Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bonn, December 7 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder Monday disagreed with Greek Prime Minister Kostas
Simitis over Bonn's demands for a cut to its European Union budget
bill, which will be an issue of dispute for the bloc's Vienna
summit later this week.
</P>
<P>
"There are clear differences of opinion," said Schroeder at
news briefing with Simitis after his talks with the Greek leader.
</P>
<P>
Germany is the biggest European Union paymaster and wants to
slash his net annual EU contribution. An agreement must be reached
by the end of 1999 when the EU's current financial arrangements
expire.
</P>
<P>
Bonn wants to cut EU spending on farm subsidies and reform
infrastructure development aid as a means to finance its budget
rebate. Greece, as one of the EU members which has profited from
both programs, is opposed to that.
</P>
<P>
"We are at the bottom of the scale," said Simitis. He holds EU
should continue capital transfers from the EU's northern states to
the southern members. "Europe must not only be politically united
but must also have economic unity if it is to hold together",
Simitis said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Germany's calls to freeze the EU budget, Simitis
said: "We are of a different opinion. We do not believe freezing
the budget would help."
</P>
<P>
But Simitis expressed optimism that agreement could be reached
on the so-called Agenda 2000 reform which covers revamping the
budget, farm subsidies and infrastructure aid.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that despite the different interests solutions can
always be found," he said.
</P>
<P>
Germany will take over the rotating E.U. presidency for the
first half of 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
