<HEADLINE> Namibian PM in Tanzania to Enhance Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Namibian Prime Minister
Hage Geingob arrived in Dar es Salaam Monday for a three-day
state visit to Tanzania, to boost bilateral relations especially
in trade.
</P>
<P>
Geingob was greeted at the Dar es Salaam International Airport
by his Tanzanian counterpart Frederick Sumaye, as well as Foreign
Minister Jakaya Kikwete and other senior government officials.
</P>
<P>
He was then driven to the Sheraton Hotel in the city for a
private lunch before holding official talks with Prime Minister
Sumaye in the afternoon. An official dinner is arranged for him
in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Geingob will visit the Dar es Salaam port Tuesday and then fly
to Zanzibar isles for an overnight stay, according to a program
issued by the foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
He will come back to Dar es Salaam where he is expected to
attend celebrations to mark Tanzania's Independence Day Wednesday
at the National Stadium before flying to Johannesburg in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
His delegation includes Minister for Finance Nangolo Mbumba,
Minister for Tourism Phillemon Malima, Deputy Minister for Higher
Education Buddy Wentworth, Deputy Minister for Information and
Broadcasting Ignatius Shixhuameni and SWAPO Deputy Secretary for
Transport Maxton Joseph.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the Namibian Prime Minister will also pay a
courtesy call on Tanzania's former President Julius Nyerere, a
veteran African statesman.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian foreign ministry officials said the visit of
Namibian Premier is expected to consolidate bilateral ties in the
political, economic, social and cultural domains.
</P>
<P>
The two countries had excellent politico-diplomatic relations
dating back to the 1960s when the Namibian people were struggling
for their national liberation with Dar es Salaam serving as the
rear base.
</P>
<P>
Geingob's visit will stimulate investments and commercial
relations between Tanzania and Namibia, both of which have a lot
to share in terms of trade in various commodities such as coffee,
cashewnuts and rice as well as experiences in fishery and mining
sectors, a foreign ministry statement said.
</P>
<P>
Before arriving in Dar es Salaam, the Namibian prime minister
paid a private visit to north Tanzania viewing game in the
Olduvai Gorge and Ngorongoro Crater at the weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
