<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greater European Role on Cyprus Issue Underlined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Council of Europe (CE)
can make greater contribution towards a solution of the Cyprus
problem, Andras Barsony, President of the Political Committee of
Council's Parliamentary Assembly, said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Barsony, after calling on Cyprus' President Glafcos Clerides
and House of Representatives President Spyros Kyprianou, said,
"Probably the key issue of the solution is a much wider and much
more effective guarantee, on both the security and civilian side."
</P>
<P>
Barsony said he had a "very fruitful" exchange of views with
Cyprus' President on "the elements of a possible solution".
</P>
<P>
Referring to the CE role, Barsony said it "should be much
more significant on the civilian side", as it is not a security
organization.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the existing guarantors of Cyprus' independence
(Britain, Greece and Turkey) could be replaced by the NATO, he
said "it could be a future option, of course it depends on the
parties".
</P>
<P>
He said that experience of the past 25 to 30 years have shown
that more security is needed on Cyprus and that Greece and Turkey
"transferred" their differences here.
</P>
<P>
"A wider international guarantee would put out the issue of
the continuous Turkish-Greek conflict from the island's political
life," Barsony added.
</P>
<P>
Barsony also pointed out that non-NATO members who have
fundamental interests in the region, such as Russia, should also
have a role.
</P>
<P>
CE, with 32 members, was founded in May 1949 to achieve a
greater unity between its members and to facilitate their economic
and social progress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
