<HEADLINE> Gulf Summit Opens to Boost Regional Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The 19th session of the
summit of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) opened here Monday
evening to explore ways to cement regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the six member states of the GCC will review the
recent developments in the region and seek unified stands in
various fields at the three-day summit.
</P>
<P>
The annual summit was also represented by leaders from outside
the group, the first time since the group was set up in 1981.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General kofi Annan, South African President
Nelson Mandela, Secretary General of Arab League Ahmed Esmat
Abdel-Meguild, Secretary General of Organization of Islamic
Conference Ezzidine Laraki will attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance, groups
Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab
Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The six states are in joint possession of nearly 45 percent of
the world's oil deposits and 15 percent of its natural gas
reserves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
