<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Hopes to See All Human Beings Enjoy Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday voiced his hope to see that "all human beings
enjoys their human rights."
</P>
<P>
To safeguard Human Rights "is our challenge," he said. "To make
every day matter in the fight to broaden the horizon of human
rights until that day when no man is tortured, no woman is abused
and no child is denied his dignity -- when all human beings enjoy
their human rights."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief made the remarks in his message on the occasion
of the 50th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human
Rights, to be observed on December 10, which also coincides with
the World Human Rights Day.
</P>
<P>
"Human Rights Day 1998 marks the 50th anniversary of the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights," Annan said. "Today, we
celebrate the half-century of a United Nations milestone."
</P>
<P>
"Human Rights Day 1998 is a day for all of us who enjoy human
rights to imagine life without them -- and to think how hard we
would fight to retain them," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is a day for us to recall not only the rights attained
over 50 years, but also the rights denied; to pursue the
achievement of justice by all and for all; to defend against the
abuse of human rights with greater vigilance persistence than
ever," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. figures, 1.5 billion people must get by on
less than 1 U.S. dollar a day. In South Asia, half of all children
under 5 are malnourished. Only a third of the people in
sub-Saharan Africa are likely to live past 40.
</P>
<P>
"It is the day to renew our commitment to globalizing justice
in the age of globalization," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Rights have been asserted where regimes once ruled; justice
has been delivered where impunity once reigned; and memory has
been honored where the powerful once enjoyed immunity," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan's statement came as the world is marking the 50th
anniversary this week of the Universal Declaration of Human
Rights.
</P>
<P>
Adopted on December 10, 1948, in the aftermath of World War II,
the declaration was designed to prevent a repetition of the
horrors of the Holocaust and other atrocities.
</P>
<P>
Beginning with the pronouncement that "all human beings are born
free and equal in dignity and rights," the United Nations document
set out to cover the range of human existence. It has become at
once the most quoted international document of modern times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0015 </DOCNO>
