<HEADLINE> 100 People Evacuated in North Carolina State in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Some 100 people were
evacuated after a tractor-trailer crashed along Interstate 26 and
spilled a highly volatile and toxic chemical in North Carolina
State of the United States, reports reaching here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The truck, carrying a mixed cargo including sodium
hydrosulfite, overturned Sunday afternoon and sparked a fire that
was still burning early Monday. Troopers closed a 13-kilometer
stretch of the interstate in western North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Department of Transportation describes sodium
hydrosulfite as a corrosive, spontaneously combustible material
that can burn skin and eyes. It is used in bleaching paper pulp
and in the production of leather goods.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters hoped to let the fire burn itself out, but they
worried that rain forecast for Monday could make matters worse.
The chemical can react explosively when it comes into contact with
water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
