<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Health Delivery System Decentralized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Health and Child
Welfare Minister Timothy Stamps Monday said his ministry was
working on decentralizing the health system in areas designated
under the government land redistribution program.
</P>
<P>
Stamps was officiating at a donation ceremony from the
Zimbabwean representative of the United Nations Population Fund
(UNFPA) aimed at reinforcing the health delivery systems in the
resettled areas, the Zimbabwe News Agency Ziana reported.
</P>
<P>
Although the land redistribution program had been left for too
long, his ministry still had hope the Health for All by the Year
2000 vision could be achieved if services were decentralized to
the resettled areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The ministry wants to decentralize the health system in the
resettlement areas so that people settled there do not rely on
health facilities in major centers," said Stamps.
</P>
<P>
The assistance from UNFPA would be used in the improvement of
the health delivery system in resettlement areas.
</P>
<P>
Stamps received five million Zimbabwean Dollars (about 140,000
U.S. Dollars) from the UNFPA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
