<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The 19th summit of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) opened here Monday evening with an aim
to cementing regional cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
The GCC was set up in Abu Dhabi in May 1981 when the leaders of
Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab
Emirates held their first summit.
</P>
<P>
The alliance was intended to enhance coordination, cooperation
and unification in all fields of the six member states in the
strategic and oil-rich Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
One of its main targets is to establish a common market, to
unify customs duties, industrial policies and investment laws as
well as to set up a unified currency.
</P>
<P>
The GCC has three main structures, namely the Supreme Council,
the Ministerial Council and the Secretariat General based in
Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the group meet once a year to develop their plans
for collective security and economic unity.
</P>
<P>
The six countries produce nearly 13.5 million barrels of oil
each day, or one fifth of the world's total. Their oil reserves,
which are estimated at 465 billion barrels, account for 45 percent
of the total global oil resources.
</P>
<P>
The GCC members, whose economy depends heavily on oil earnings,
have suffered a hard hit in the current oil price slump resulting
from oversupply and flagging demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Incidence of Childhood Asthma in Greece Increases Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The incidence of childhood
asthma in Greece had increased fivefold over the past 20 years
mainly due to parent smoke and bad ventilation, according to the
findings of a study released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The study, which was recently conducted by the Greek Pulmonary
Society in Iraklion, Thessaloniki and Ioannina, showed that about
two in 10 Greek children suffered from asthma attacks.
</P>
<P>
In the southern Greek island of Crete, the number of primary
school students suffering asthma attacks after gymnastic sessions
was triple the number of the other two regions. This appeared to
be due to either to genetic reasons or to the fact that the warm
climate on the island contributed to the spread of allergens,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
Asthma was more prevalent in urban centers, but still present
in rural regions, where certain crops could bring about an asthma
attack.
</P>
<P>
Kostis Kotordis, president of the society, said that smog was
just not able to create as serious a problem as cigarette smoke.
</P>
<P>
Homes were not aired properly, allowing allergens in dust to
circulate, a problem that had increased with advent of double
glazed windows, experts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
