<HEADLINE> U.S. Official Hails Lebanese New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting United States
Secretary of Health and Human Services Donna Shalala Monday
praised the formation of the Lebanese new government and voiced
U.S. support for the new regime.
</P>
<P>
"Everything that I've heard and seen in Lebanon leads me to
report to the president (Bill Clinton) how much promise and
enthusiasm there is for the government," Shalala said after a
meeting with Lebanese President Emile Lahoud.
</P>
<P>
"We had a very good meeting with President Lahoud. We
transmitted to him the president's strong support for him and
his government, and how impressed we were with his cabinet
appointments," she added.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud, 62, a former army commander, took over from his
predecessor Elias Hrawi last month. He designated Lebanon's
four-time prime minister Salim Hoss as the new head of government
last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 16-man new cabinet announced by Hoss three days ago was
made up of many fresh faces, a government described by local media
as "clean and honest" in contrast to the previous one charged with
corruption.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process and the issue of south
Lebanon, Shalala said the U.S. is committed to a comprehensive
peace and settlement in the region which will also cover
south Lebanon issue.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a self-declared security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north
from cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting
against Israel's occupation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
