<HEADLINE> French President Calls for Respect of Cultural Diversity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Monday called for the respect of cultural diversity and dialogue
when dealing with the issue of human rights.
</P>
<P>
In a speech made to the UNESCO marking the 50th anniversary of
the birth of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights in Paris,
Chirac said that the fight for human rights remains a "violent
reality."
</P>
<P>
"We don't succeed either through containment, nor by giving
lessons. It is through dialogue, cooperation and technical
assistance that we move ahead," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that although the fight for human rights has brought
about fruits, the principles proclaimed by the Declaration 50
years ago are still being mocked at.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that the fight for human rights is also one of
"economic fight" because economic development and democracy go
hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that "an agenda on globalization" be submitted to
the United Nations General Assembly before 2000 to establish
economic, social and judicial rules around the world.
</P>
<P>
"Freedom without law, it is absolute power of the strong over
the weak. It is the incumbent duty of the international community
to work out the rules of this new world order," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chirac warned against the negative effects coming down from the
modern information technologies such as the information highway
being developed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
He also warned French citizens against the danger of racism and
xenophobia which are being promoted by forces such as the National
Front.  
</P>
</TEXT>
