<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Calls for Further OPEC Output Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Oil Minister Bijan
Namdar Zanganeh Monday called for a further cut in the output
ceiling of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countriies
(OPEC).
</P>
<P>
"Iran wants a reduction of 1.5 million barrels per day (bpd) or
higher in OPEC's output ceiling," Zanganeh was quoted by the
official news agency IRNA as saying.
</P>
<P>
Zanganeh's appeal came amid reports that Iran and Saudi Arabia,
the two oil producing giants in the Persian Gulf, have held
consultations aimed at recovering the sluggish oil market.
</P>
<P>
Before a year-end meeting of the OPEC in Vienna in November,
Zanganeh held talks with his Saudi counterpart Ali al-Naimi on
ways to lift the sagging oil prices. But they failed to work out
any measures.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's average oil price has been cut nearly by half over the
past year because of a global oil glut brought on by its ill-timed
decision last winter to boost production, coinciding with Asia's
economic crisis and falling demands.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 11-nation oil cartel failed to achieve a further
output cut at the Vienna meeting due to the internal differences
among its member states.
</P>
<P>
Zanganeh did not comment on talks between Iranian and Saudi
officials, but said that Iran produces crude oil according to its
OPEC-determined quota and has so far observed the reduction in its
crude output.
</P>
<P>
Iran's quota is 3.94 million bpd according to the OPEC decision
in November last year, and its current production was reported at
around 3.6 million bpd after the OPEC agreed to a cut of 2.6
million bpd earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Iranian leaders have recently urged the OPEC members to
cooperate closely in order to save the flagging oil prices.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the OPEC may discuss measures for the
further output cut before its next group meeting in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
