<HEADLINE> Uganda Trying to Get More From Donors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is trying to get more
than 2,000 million U.S. Dollars from its donors to support the
country's socio-economic programs in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed at the high-profile World Bank-organized
Consultative Group Meeting, popularly known as the donors'
meeting being held in Sheraton Hotel here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Our total financing gap is 2,176 million U.S. Dollars over
three years of which 1,191 million Dollars will be met from money
already committed and 985 million Dollars is what we require them
(the donors) to commit themselves to this week," Secretary to the
Treasury Emannuel Tumusiime Metebile said.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference has drawn delegates from more than 20
countries and more than 20 funding agencies. President Yoweri
Museveni is expected to address the conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Although the Ugandan government is asking for more donations,
most of the donors are pressing for more accountability of their
donated money and urges the government to combat corruption.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports that as Uganda is developing its
economy at a rare rate, quite a big sum of the donated money has
been embezzled by corrupt officials in the government.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has gotten more than 800 million Dollars from donors in
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
