<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Speed up Railways Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- African States are urged
Monday to achieve adequate development policy and pursue and
accelerate the restructuring process of the railway sector.
</P>
<P>
The call is made by Omer M.M. Nour, President of the Union of
African Railways (UAR), at the opening ceremony of the four-day
26th general assembly held at the United Nations Conference
Center here.
</P>
<P>
The president said that economic development and commercial
relationship between States and regions have changed to a
world-wide system including liberalization of the transport
system based in a competition between different modes.
</P>
<P>
"The UAR should sum up and analyze the different experiences
on restructuring," he says, adding that "the restructuring of the
railways companies and their transformation into market oriented
commercial enterprises should be willingly, persistently and
rigorously carried out."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, A.M.A. Dirar, Director of Economic
Development and Cooperation Department of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), says privatization and commercialization of
railway operations are now strong on the agenda of many African
governments and are regarded as the major solutions to the
problems of undercapitalization and inefficiency in the railways.
</P>
<P>
This is a new concept not only in Africa, but also worldwide,
he said, adding that the UAR needs to address this issue
critically and assist its members in carrying out the
privatization process successfully.
</P>
<P>
The growing private sector participation in railway business
will influence membership and decision making in the UAR, he
said, hoping the UAR to re-examine and re-shape itself so as to
be able to meet the challenges of today in the railway
sub-sector.
</P>
<P>
The four-day UAR annual meeting will hold deliberations
focusing on the ways of privatizing African Railways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
