<HEADLINE> Greece to Meet all EMU Entry Criteria, Says Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Greece would meet all the
economic targets that would allow Athens' entry into the European
Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) by January 1, 2001, a Greek bank
official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a conference held by the Hellenic-American Chamber,
the National Bank of Greece Governor Theodoros Karatzas said that
Greece was a stone's throw away from meeting EMU entry criteria.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Greek stock market had made a healthy
contribution to the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Athens Stock Exchange's capitalization at the end of
October stood at more than 58 billion U.S. dollars despite a
global financial crisis, up from 34.7 billion dollars at the end
of 1997, he added.
</P>
<P>
The governor said that the Athens bourse had also enjoyed a
higher rate of growth than other markets in Europe and worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Greece's National Economy and Finance Minister Yannos
Papantoniou also expressed optimism that Greece would realize its
goal of joining the EMU in 2001.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time in post-war that a Greek government was
attaining its targets, he said, adding that this had boosted
Greece's international credibility and resulted in international
financial organizations taking Greece's EMU entry for granted and
recommending to their clients to purchase Greek state securities.
</P>
</TEXT>
