<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Okayed to Reoccupy U.N. Seat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The 53rd General
Assembly (GA) session on Monday morning adopted by consensus a
Credentials Committee recommendation for Cambodia to reclaim its
U.N. seat, a spokesperson for the GA President announced.
</P>
<P>
Jadranka Mihalic, the spokesperson, told a press conference
that the GA plenary session adopted a special report by the
Credentials Committee on the credentials of Cambodia, and the
Cambodian delegation is seated at the General Assembly after its
seat remains vacant for 15 months.
</P>
<P>
The adoption was made without a vote, she said.
</P>
<P>
The Credentials Committee cleared the way on Friday last week
for Cambodia to reoccupy its U.N. seat after the committee acted
without a vote and without any speeches at a closed-door meeting
that lasted only a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
The GA made the decision after the swear-in of the new
Cambodian coalition government on November 30, which is headed
by Prime Minister Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan issued a statement, voicing
his welcome to the new government in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
On December 2, Cambodia's Head of State King Norodom Sihanouk
sent Annan a letter naming Cambodia's new U.N. delegation.
</P>
<P>
Those credentials named Ouch Borith, previously Cambodia's
deputy permanent representative to the United Nations, as the new
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
The Credentials Committee decided in September 1997 to leave
Cambodia's seat vacant when it was claimed by rival factions
following a coup two months earlier in which First Prime Minister
Prince Norodom Ranariddh was unseated by co-premier Hun Sen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
