<HEADLINE> IRA Holds Major Policy Army Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Irish Republican Army (IRA)
has held a full session of its ruling Army Council to assess the
continuing impasse over decommissioning terrorist arms, BBC
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paramilitary group reportedly held the meeting over the
weekend in County Cavan, not far from the Irish Republic's border
with Northern Ireland, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The IRA has recently denied that it was planning such a
meeting, and rejected reports that it would discuss arms
decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
The failure of groups including the IRA to decommission arms
has led to fears that the peace process in the province may
falter.
</P>
<P>
Last week talks between Northern Ireland parties at Stormont
Castle on the establishment of cross-border bodies and an
executive body on the new Northern Ireland Assembly stalled amid
wrangling over arms decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Ireland First Minister, David Trimble, has said he
would not allow Sinn Fein to take up seats in the executive, until
the IRA begins to give up weapons.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein is equally adamant that it has a right to be sit on
the executive regardless of what the IRA does.
</P>
<P>
In a separate development, British Prime Minister Tony Blair
and his Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern held a 15-minute telephone
discussion on Monday about the hold-up in the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders plan to contact the various parties over the
next few days in a bid to force progress before Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
