<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6 African States Discuss Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from six
African countries are gathering here Monday to discuss how to
improve learning in rural primary schools of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Ethiopia, Guinea, Mali, Senegal, Uganda
and Zambia as well as representatives from bilateral and
multilateral agencies are participating in the five-day workshop
beginning Monday.
</P>
<P>
The main objectives of the workshop are to gain better
understanding of processes which help improve learning outcomes
in rural primary schools; to provide a forum in which the
participants contribute to the exchange of experiences and to
generate new ideas for action.
</P>
<P>
In a speech read on his behalf at the workshop, Zambian
Education Minister Godfrey Miyanda said population growth and a
heavy debt burden are factors, among others, which are slowing
down socio-economic development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said rapid population growth means not only a short-term
sacrifice of per capita income growth but also tighter
constraints in extending education.
</P>
<P>
In most cases the rural area is the most affected, he said.
</P>
<P>
Up till 1966 the education cycle in Zambia consisted of seven
years of primary education, five years of secondary education and
four year of higher education, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said in the new national policy on education the government
has adopted a new system in which every Zambian child will have
nine years of basic education (7-5-4).
</P>
<P>
The breakdown is grades one to four lower basic, grade five to
seven middle basic, grade eight to nine upper basic and grade 10
to 12 high school with the last four years being for higher
education (9-3-4), Miyanda said.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is one of a number of activities which the United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization
(UNESCO) and the World Bank are organizing within the framework
of the more comprehensive U.N. Special Initiative for Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
