<HEADLINE> Sudan's Opposition Group to Hold Meeting in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A Sudanese opposition leader said
here Monday that the National Democratic Alliance (NDA) of Sudan
will discuss possible actions against the government in a meeting
in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa,
former Sudanese Prime Minister al-Sadeq al-Mahdi said the NDA
meeting will come in light of the need for an understanding at the
highest level of the group.
</P>
<P>
But he did not specify the date of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the meeting, he discussed with Moussa the
situation in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
NDA, an umbrella group of Sudan's opposition factions, includes
the Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA), a major rebel group in
the south, led by John Garang, and the Ummah Party, led by
al-Mahdi.
</P>
<P>
SPLA has been fighting since 1983 to press for increased
autonomy for the southern third of Sudan, which is mainly African,
Christian and animist, from the Muslim government.
</P>
<P>
SPLA and the Sudanese government have held several rounds of
talks on autonomy in the south, but failed to reach an agreement
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Al-Mahdi said that NDA leaders will also hold talks with
Egyptian officials in a bid to consult with Egypt on the Sudanese
issues.
</P>
<P>
Al-Mahdi expressed appreciation for Egypt's key role in helping
resolving the Sudanese issue, saying that "the time has come for
the Egyptian role to contain the Sudanese crisis."
</P>
<P>
Egypt hosted a similar meeting of NDA in August, which was
opposed by Sudan.
</P>
<P>
But Egypt argued that its move was aimed at helping secure
Sudan's territorial integrity. It fears that a possible
disintergration of the southern neighbor could endanger the Nile
River, its main source of water.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Egypt and Sudan soured in 1995 after
Cairo accused Khartoum of masterminding an assassination attempt
against President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
Egypt also accused Sudan of harboring Islamic militants, who
attempt to topple the Egyptian secular government and install a
strict Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has denied both charges.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming meeting of Sudanese rebel groups is announced at a
time when a thaw in the ties seems to have set in after the two
sides expressed readiness to improve the bilateral relations and
exchanged visits by senior officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
