<HEADLINE> U.N. Sanctions Create Losses of 23 Billion Dollars: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Libya told the United
Nations in a report issued here on Monday that it had lost some
23.64 billion U.S. dollars by the end of last year in the wake of
sanctions imposed since 1992 in connection with the Lockerbie
airliner bombings.
</P>
<P>
"The financial losses sustained since the sanctions were
imposed on April 15, 1992, continue to mount," the 21-page report
said, "As at December 31, 1997, they came to roughly
23,641,923,728 U.S. dollars."
</P>
<P>
The Libyan report listed such most-affected sectors, which
suffered "enormous damage in terms of human and material loss," as
health, agriculture, animal husbandry, transport, industry,
economy and energy.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed by the U.N. Security Council because
of Libya's failure to hand over for trial in Britain or the United
States the two Libyans accused of planting a bomb aboard a Pan Am
airliner that exploded over the Scottish town of Lockerbie on
December 21, 1988, killing 270 people.
</P>
<P>
The Sanctions, broadened in 1993, include a ban on
international flights to and from Libya, an arms embargo, a
downgrading of diplomatic ties, a freeze on some Libyan assets
abroad. However, there is no embargo on oil exports, the main
earner of foreign exchange for Libya.
</P>
<P>
In August this year, Tripoli offered cooperation with London
and Washington by agreeing to hold the trial of the two suspects
by a Scottish court in the Netherlands, but it refused to let the
two Libyans, if convicted, to serve their sentences in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who flew to Libya for a
meeting on Saturday with Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi, failed to
bring a solution to the long-standing issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
