<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Forms Long-Term Strategy to Boost Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt said Monday that it has
formulated a strategy till the year 2010 to promote economic
growth while bringing down the unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
Under the strategy, Egypt is expected to raise its the annual
economic growth rate to 7 percent while bringing the unemployment
rate to less than 3 percent, Minister of State for Planning Zafer
el-Beshri told a forum here organized by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
El-Beshri said that his country has removed hurdles hindering
foreign investments and is expediting economic reforms to increase
the growth rate, Egyptian Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Egypt started economic reforms in 1991, featuring privatization
of state-run enterprises. One third of the 314 chosen state
enterprises have been sold under the reform program, sponsored by
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The reform program, which was carried out in three stages from
1991 to 1998, was designed to upgrade Egypt's financial and
currency systems and expand the role of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has offered Egypt a total of 4.5 billion dollars
in long-term loans since 1970, el-Beshri said.
</P>
<P>
After years of efforts, Egypt's gross domestic product has
grown from 2 percent to the current 5 percent, inflation fallen
from 20 percent to below 5 percent and foreign currency reserves
climbed to 20 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But privatization also caused the rise of unemployment. The
International Labor Organization (ILO) said last month in a report
that that 11.3 percent of Egypt's 17.7 million labor force are out
of work.
</P>
<P>
ILO maintained that Egypt has to sustain an annual economic
growth rate of 6 percent over the next five years to pull down the
unemployment rate to 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
During his speech at the forum, Kamal Darwish, vice president
of the World Bank for the Middle East and North Africa, spoke
highly of the success Egypt has achieved in the economic reforms
and the cooperation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
He also said the bank will continue cooperation with Egypt
and go on with financing the country's development projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Deletes Iran, Malaysia from List of Drug Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton,
showing fresh gesture to Iran for possible improvement of
relations between the two countries, on Monday removed Iran from
its annual list of drug problem countries.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to members of Congress, Clinton said Iran had been
removed from the list after the United States concluded that Iran
had carried out a successful program to eradicate cultivation of
opium poppies.
</P>
<P>
While Iran continues to serve as a transit point for opiates
heading for Europe, there is no evidence to suggest that
significant quantities arrive in the United States, Clinton said
in the letter.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also deleted Malaysia from the list on grounds that the
country has not been used significantly as a transit point for
U.S.-bound drugs.
</P>
<P>
By deleting Iran and Malaysia, the list of drug problem
countries was reduced to 28.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton said in the letter that the two countries still
bear watching as the drug traffic could resume or even increase as
the region recovers.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's decision to write off Iran from the drug list came at
a time when the administration is reaching out to Iran, attempting
to establish a political dialogue for the first time in almost two
decades. But officials insisted that politics did not intervene in
the president's decision.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman David Leavy said the removal was based on
a precise legal determination under a 1961 law, and did not
reflect any larger issues in U.S.-Iranian relations, which have
thawed slightly under Iranian President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
"It did not include any political consideration," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Republican Senator Charles Grassley and
Representative Benjamin Gilman expressed concern over news
reports suggesting possible removal of Iran from the drug list.
</P>
<P>
They said in a letter to Clinton that any effort to remove Iran
from the list is not based on substantive grounds but on the
"speculative hope that such a unilateral gesture will win
diplomatic points in Iran for some anticipated rapprochement."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
