<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. Africa Conf on River Blindness Opens in Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian Vice-President John
Evans Atta Mills Monday called for collaborative efforts to
sustain the gains of the Onchocerciasis control program (OCP) to
eradicate river blindness from the sub-region, especially Ghana.
</P>
<P>
"It is crucial that we mop up every remaining small pocket of
infection," Mills told the opening session of the 19th Joint
Program Committee (JPC) of the Onchocerciasis Control Program
(OCP) in West Africa.
</P>
<P>
The one-week conference, sponsored by Ghana's ministry of
health, the Onchocerciasis Secretariat and the World Health
Organization (WHO), is being attended by health ministers and
representatives from eight countries in the sub-region, as well
as by affiliated international organizations, a special story
sent by Ghana News Agency (GNA) to Xinhua here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The JPC is made up of experts to draw action plans for the OCP
toward effective control of the disease of river blindness.
</P>
<P>
The conference is also to take stock of activities of the
program and assess preparations so far made by participating
countries to fully take over the responsibilities of the OCP
after its withdrawal by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Reports show that prevalence of the disease, which was put at
between 80 and 90 percent in 1974 has been drastically reduced to
between zero and 50 percent at present.
</P>
<P>
Onchocerciasis, also known as river blindness, is caused by
small worms that are passed on to people through the bite of the
black fly.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the symptoms of the disease include intense body
itching, development of leopard skin, painless nodules and poor
vision.
</P>
<P>
Mills expressed the hope that given the technology, support
and right leadership and motivation, joint inter-state or
sub-regional efforts can work effectively for the common good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
