<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Stresses Partnership Between U.N., GCC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 7 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan stressed Monday the importance of the partnership between
the U.N. and the Gulf cooperation Council (GCC).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the GCC summit here, Annan
said that "the partnership between the U.N. and GCC is of the
utmost importance -- especially in the field of peacemaking and
preventive diplomacy."
</P>
<P>
"The global challenge we face in today's world requires the
international community to build bridges across regions and
sub-regions," he said, adding that "these bridges are two-way
avenues for cooperation in which every country can and must play
its part within its means and its areas of strength."
</P>
<P>
Annan, the first U.N. chief to attend the GCC summit, said
Regional organizations such as the GCC are U.N.'s most important
partners and allies. "They serve to both complement and support
the U.N.'s work," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the Iraqi issue, Annan said that the only way to lift the
U.N. sanctions on Iraq "is for Iraq to comply fully with the
relevant resolutions of the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
"I was saddened and burdened, therefore, by the Iraqi decision
in October not to cooperate with the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM)," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Iraq narrowly averted a U.S. military strike in the last minute
in November by backing down from its decision and to resume
cooperation with UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
On the peace process between Israel and the Palestinians, the
U.N. chief expressed hope that the Wye agreement signed recently
"will be implemented in all its aspects and will pave the way for
the resumption of negotiations on all tracks."
</P>
<P>
Under the Wye agreement, Israel will pull out its troops from
another 13 percent of the West Bank in return for tougher
Palestinian actions against Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to all parties concerned to make efforts in
pursuing a lasting solution to the conflict between Israel and
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Annan noted that violence launched by elements opposed to
the peace process have continued to cost lives and mar progress.
"They must be condemned," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
