<HEADLINE> Iran to Test Electronic System for Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced on Monday an
electronic system to guide missiles or deviate their direction
will be tested in the ongoing Vahdat-77 (Unity-77) naval
maneuvers in the Persian Gulf and the Gulf of Oman.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the maneuver Issa Golverdi told the official
news agency IRNA that in testing application of the mechanism
for deviating the missile direction, real missiles will be
deployed in the operational zones.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the coming two days, the system, named as
Mersad (Ambush), will be tested in both static and dynamic
fields.
</P>
<P>
Defensive readiness against missile threats from the other
side of the region is the main motive behind
research work on the electronic system, Golverdi said.
</P>
<P>
He said the deployment of the system plays a key role in
preserving security, interests and vital resources of the Islamic
Republic of Iran in the Persian Gulf and the Gulf of Oman.
</P>
<P>
The five-day military exercises kicked off in the
Persian Gulf waters on Friday. Golverdi said that several stages
of the maneuver have been successfully carried out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
