<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Markets Fade as Wall St Fails to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- A European share rally faded
Monday despite a bullish performance overnight in Asia and a surge
on Wall Street last Friday.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 ended slightly weaker as investors remained
on hold ahead of the Bank of England's rate-setting meeting later
in the week.
</P>
<P>
A Reuters poll of economists showed 23 out of 26 expected a
rate cut of at least 25 basis points. The FTSE 100 index closed
5.2 points, or 0.1 percent, down at 5,576.7 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market had drifted in a state of torpor as
early impetus from overnight rallies in New York and Hong Kong
faded.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Xetra Dax index fell after early gains, with a lack
of signals to inspire the market preventing a traditional year-end
rally, traders said.
</P>
<P>
By 1515 GMT the electronically traded Xetra Dax was down 1.9
percent at 4,709.37 points. The floor Dax fell 1.2 percent to
4,718.93 points.
</P>
<P>
Traders in the Frankfurt market said that with a pan-European
interest rate cut last week, the prospect of another market
boosting near-term rate cut had been quashed.
</P>
<P>
Paris stocks closed up 0.87 percent after the Dow's bullish
performance Friday failed to follow through at start of trade on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The Cac 40 index closed up 32.63 points at 3,771.22 after
peaking at 3,794.94 earlier in the session.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the lackluster session to a lack of
investor interest, scant corporate news and preparations for euro
launch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
