<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European, American Pillars Should Both Develop: Cook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook on Tuesday called on European Union countries to
develop a common defense policy working in tandem with the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the NATO foreign ministers council meeting, Cook
said that the Europeans should have the ability to react when
their interest and security were threatened.
</P>
<P>
Britain and France have joined in fostering a dialogue on
common European Union defense policy with the signing of an
agreement last week at Saint-Malo.
</P>
<P>
The British foreign secretary said that both the European and
American pillars within NATO should contribute toward the security
of the Euro-Atlantic area.
</P>
<P>
However, it was time for Europe to make its contribution by
restructuring the European pillar, to render it usable not only in
collective defense operations, but in crisis management,
peacekeeping and humanitarian missions as well.
</P>
<P>
He said that no one or two European countries could monopolize
the EU on the issue of a common European defense policy. The
common EU defense policy needed transparency, tolerance and
enthusiasm to work, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is essential to pursue the European Security and Defense
Identity (ESDI) together," stressed the British foreign secretary.
</P>
<P>
The ESDI concept was first developed during the 1994 NATO
council at heads of state and government level and aims at
developing European defense capability within the framework of
NATO.
</P>
<P>
NATO has expressed its preparedness to allow European member
states to use the alliance's assets and capabilities in their own
operations.
</P>
<P>
But, Cook stressed, there would be no point if European members
failed to contribute to NATO military effectiveness in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
Cook, whose country is one of the three nuclear states within
NATO, said that he did not see the need for a change in the
alliance's nuclear deterrence doctrine that has been the core of
NATO strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
The United States and France are the other two nuclear states
in the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, German Foreign Minister Joschka Fisher and Canadian
Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy both publicly announced their
support for a no-first-use policy.
</P>
<P>
A NATO official said after the council meeting that a growing
consensus was building up among NATO decision-makers that any
change would have to make both military as well as political
sense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
