<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haitian Exiles in France Call for Trial of Former Dictator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Haitians living in exile in
France and several French college professors have set up a
committee calling for the trial of former Haitian dictator
Jean-Claude Duvalier, otherwise known as "Baby Doc", for crimes
against humanity during his rule from 1971 to 1986.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted Gerald Bloncourt, a Haitian
journalist, as saying that "the Committee for the Prosecution of
Duvalier" was created in Paris to coincide with the 50th
anniversary of the Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
Duvalier, 47, fled Haiti to France in 1986 in the wake of
several weeks of riots in his country.
</P>
<P>
He and his father, Francois Duvalier, ruled Haiti with an iron
fist symbolized by the death squad "Tontons Macoutes".
</P>
<P>
Duvalier, who is living near Paris in a house rented by his
relatives and is without residency papers or income, has been
rarely seen in public since his mother died a year ago in a clinic
in the Paris region, according to AFP.
</P>
<P>
The French Interior Ministry said that it had no information on
the situation of Duvalier, who has been refused the status of
political refugee by the French Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
His lawyer, Sauveur Vaisse, said that Duvalier was in France
two weeks ago and was very probably still in the country.
</P>
<P>
So far no warrant of arrest or extradition request has been
made against Duvalier, said French officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
