<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF: Education Crisis Poses Threat on Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of millions of children
are growing up without good basic education, posing a threat to
global peace and prosperity, the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) warned in an annual report released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF pointed out that modern technology is unprecedentedly
providing people with access to information, but it has widened
the gap between the rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
"The tragedy is that the technological advances have further
deepened the gap between the rich and poor, and between those
sufficiently affluent and educated to benefit from the new
learning technology and those disqualified by poverty and
illiteracy," said The State of the World's Children 1999 report.
</P>
<P>
Carol Bellamy, UNICEF executive director, who is here for the
launch of the report, urged international cooperation in promoting
children's education.
</P>
<P>
Describing poverty and mounting debts as strangling developing
countries attempts to provide education for children, she urged
the developed countries to review the debts of developing
countries and to provide them with development assistance.
</P>
<P>
To achieve education for all children, the world needed to
spend an additional seven billion U.S. dollars per year over the
next decade, according to the report. "This is less than the
annual spending of Americans on cosmetics, or Europeans on
ice-cream." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
