<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newcastle United in Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- English Premier League club
Newcastle United was thrown back into turmoil when chairman Denis
Cassidy quit Newcastle United on Tuesday after controversial
directors Douglas Hall and Freddy Shepherd were restored to the
main company board.
</P>
<P>
Cassidy, a lifelong Newcastle fan who was appointed to the
position five months ago, stepped down with fellow non-executive
directors John Josephs and Tom Fenton after they were outvoted on
the Hall and Shepherd issue on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The trio said they felt they could not continue in the
circumstances and the premier league club also said BT Alex.Brown
had resigned as the company's stockbrokers.
</P>
<P>
The departures were the latest in a long line of boardroom
upsets to bedevil Newcastle since the club was floated on the
stock market in April last year.
</P>
<P>
Shepherd and Hall were forced to step down earlier this year
after making controversial comments about the club's supporters
and their re-appointment prompted the resignation of the Newcastle
 plc chairman and its business advisor.
</P>
<P>
The two own a majority stake of more than 60 per cent and were
able to vote themselves back on to the board.
</P>
<P>
They were restored to the football club board -- but not the
main company board -- in late July, shortly after Cassidy had
been recruited as company chairman.
</P>
<P>
Their attempts to rejoin the main board caused a split among
directors, who voted four to three to bring them back.
</P>
<P>
John Fender, the fourth non-executive, sided with Chief
Executive Freddie Fletcher, Finance Director Les Wheatley and
Property Director Russell Jones in the vote.
</P>
<P>
BT Alex Brown, one of the City's largest stockbrokers has
ended its association with the club as a result of the boardroom
clash.
</P>
<P>
The move is likely to further damage Newcastle's already
tarnished image in the City after a terrible year for the club.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle United fell 3p, or more than 3%, to 95p on the news.
</P>
<P>
A statement to the City published today read: "Newcastle
United plc today announced the re-appointment of Douglas Hall and
Freddy Shepherd to the board of the company with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
"The company also announced that Denis Cassidy, John Josephs
and Tom Fenton felt they could not continue as chairman and
non-executive directors respectively in these circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"The Board regrets that they came to this conclusion and
wishes to extend its thanks for their past valuable contribution."
</P>
<P>
Newcastle chief executive Freddie Fletcher has agreed to
become acting chairman, pending the appointment of a new
independent non-executive chairman and non-executive director.
</P>
<P>
After the high-octane excitement of the Kevin Keegan era,
things took a downturn last season.
</P>
<P>
The club was embroiled in a public war of words with
non-league Stevenage over the venue for their FA Cup fourth round
tie.
</P>
<P>
They went on to reach Wembley but were outplayed by Arsenal
and only made sure of avoiding relegation to Division One in the
final few games of the season.
</P>
<P>
But just as damaging was a News of the World article which
claimed Shepherd and Hall had insulted the fans and dubbed star
striker Alan Shearer "Mary Poppins".
</P>
<P>
The pair stood down in the face of anger from supporters but
returned in July with the task of reviving Newcastle's fortunes
on the pitch.
</P>
<P>
A poor start to this season saw Kenny Dalglish removed as
manager and Dutchman Ruud Gullit brought in as his replacement.
</P>
<P>
He has managed to lift them to 13th in the Premiership table
and recently spent seven million pounds on Everton striker Duncan
Ferguson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
