<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Servicemen Enjoying A Better Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Things are a lot better for
Chinese soldiers these days as far as clothing, food, housing and
health-care are concerned, thanks to government efforts of the
past 20 years, military sources say.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s and early '90s, army uniforms have been changed
twice in design and materials, turning the shabby and laughable
uniform of the past into a more stylish one.
</P>
<P>
More money has been spent on improving the nutritional value of
military food to keep servicemen fit enough to deal with the harsh
military trainings and to prepare for any kind of warfare.
</P>
<P>
In the past two decades, the Central Military Commission has
increased per-capita spending on food 13 times, and, in 1984 and
1988, the military developed their own standards on nutrition and
amounts of food for military personnel.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,100 food productions bases and over 1,400 service
centers have been set up in the army at brigade or regiment
level. It still gets 70 percent of its meat and vegetable from
farms managed by soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Army headquarters have also paid more attention to improving the
housing and medical services available to soldiers, and 70 percent
of the officers have been moved into standard apartments, compared
with less than 10 percent in the late '70s. Over six billion yuan
has been spent on improving barracks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
