<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Dismayed over Lukewarm Shows in Asian Games (Day Three) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- China felt more sorrow as its
athletes still had lukewarm performances while Chinese Taipei got
every reason for cheers by taking three gold medals in the Bangkok
Asian Games on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
As trump-card swimmer Chen Yan skipped today's 200m and
tomorrow's 400m freestyles due to diarrhea, China was left
empty-handed but five silvers from the swimming pool where only
Tsai Shu-Min of Chinese Taipei stopped Japan from celebrating a
clean sweep of five golds at stake.
</P>
<P>
"Just as expected, today was our darkest day in the games,"
said Chinese head coach Zhang Xiong, "for in all the five events,
we are in disadvantage against the Japanese."
</P>
<P>
Tsai won its first Asiad's swimming gold medal for Chinese
Taipei as she clocked the fastest timing of 2:00.89 in the 200m
freestyle.
</P>
<P>
"The gold is a windfall to me, for I had no confidence to win
before the competition, and I will try my best to win more golds
in the later events," said the 18-year-old teenager who will
compete in another four disciplines.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese shooters had to hold back their tears after winning
a lonely gold out of six although coach Zhang Heng found the
execuse of "dark horses" from the men's free rifle prone events,
which, in his view, have less technical merits than on-spot
display of skills.
</P>
<P>
Japan put another five gold medals into its credit, including
the day's first gold after Akihito Udagawa rode the best in the
men's cross country race.
</P>
<P>
The other four were all from the pool as Takashi Yamamoto won
the men's 100-meter butterfly, with the first swimming Asian
record, to lead a Japanese scoop of four out of five on offer.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Japanese clocked 53.34 seconds to beat the old
mark of 53.97 set by Chinese Jiang Chengji in the last Asiad, but
still felt unhappy as "I tried to beat my personal best of 52.88,
but in vain."
</P>
<P>
Xiong Guomin, another gold hopeful for China, was later beaten
in the 400m individual medley by 18-year-old Takahiro Mori who
clocked 4:20.98 against Xiong's 4:22.57.
</P>
<P>
"Our officials encouraged us last night to beat China in the
games, which gave me energy and motivation as only the younger
generation will make the differences in future," said Mori.
</P>
<P>
Later on, Masami Tanaka, 19, won the women's 200m breaststroke
before its quartet won the last swimming gold of the day in the
men's 4x200m freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
Claiming a hope for three out of six golds, the Chinese
shooters only reapt one from the women's air pistol team event,
while the men's free rifle prone golds went to Thailand and Igor
Pirekeev of Turkmenistan respectively.
</P>
<P>
Pirekeev, an Atlanta Olympian who registered 593 points to top
the qualification, produced stable performance to lead all the way
to the title in the individual final.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's three-men squad collected a total of 1,758 to give
the host its second shooting gold following Monday's victory in
the women's air rifle.
</P>
<P>
However, China still had the most gold medals of seven as its
weightlifters and divers returned with two apiece and each from
shooting, gymnastics and cycling, all through its women athletes.
</P>
<P>
After three day's competitions, China overtook Japan for the
top position in the medal tally with 13 golds, 16 silvers and 11
bronzes, while Japan fell to second 12-9-12 and South Korea
remained in third 7-4-6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
