<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Marks 13th Charter Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) Naeem U.
Hasan hosted a reception here Tuesday evening to mark the 13th
anniversary of the signing of the SAARC Charter.
</P>
<P>
The seven-nation SAARC was established on December 8, 1985 with
the signing of the charter by the heads of state or government
from Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and
Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The charter outlines the objectives, principles and general
provisions of the regional grouping, which, among others, aim to
accelerate economic growth, social progress and cultural
development in the region.
</P>
<P>
The most significant achievement in recent years was the
operationalization in December 1995 of the SAARC Preferential
Trading Arrangement, under which three rounds of trade talks have
been completed, offering over 5,720 items of product for
preferential entry among the member countries.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC aims to set up a South Asian free trade area.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala, other senior
government officials and foreign diplomats attended the reception.
</P>
<P>
The reception also offers an opportunity for Hasan to bid
farewell as his three-year term expires at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan diplomat Nihal Rodrigo has been picked up by his
country to head the Kathmandu-based SAARC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The post of SAARC secretary general is rotated in alphabetical
order among the member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
