<HEADLINE> Japanese, Chinese Cyclists Split Cross Country Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Japanese cyclist Udagawa
Akihito won the gold medal of the men's cross country event while
Chinese girl Ma Yanping dominated the women's race at the 13th
Asian Games cycling tournament on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Udagawa clocked a winning time of two hours five minutes and
seven seconds to cover cover the five-lap, 32-kilometer route in a
scenic hillside resort in Nakornratchasima province, some 130
kilometers northeast of Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Surajit Jirojwong took advantage of his familarity
with the site and grabbed the silver in the men's race in 2:12:00,
while Chinese Li Fuyu dashed across the finish line one minute and
10 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
Li Fuyu lead a field of 13 bikers in 23:56 when he finished the
first lap, which runs 6.4 kilometers. He was followed by Thai
Surajit and Japanese Udagawa.
</P>
<P>
However, the unfortunate Chinese bumped into unexpected
trouble, as his tyre was pricked not long after the second lap
started. It took him about four minutes to change tyre, which
dragged him to the ninth place.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Udagawa took the chance to take over the lead and
maintained the first position till the end of the match.
</P>
<P>
Li successfully surpassed the several bikers from South Korea,
Hong Kong of China and his compatriot Ma Ye to finish third.
</P>
<P>
In the women's competition, Ma Yanping led the field of eight
competitors from the very beginning, and finished the four-lap
match in two hours seven minutes and 28 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Kobayashi Kanako and Thai C. Singupatham won the
silver and bronze medals in 2:11:45 and 2:17:34 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Japanese mountain bike coach Sugiyama Kiichi said after the
race that he is quite satisfied with the two golds and three
silvers in the first two days of the Asiad cycling competitions.
</P>
<P>
He expected four or five more golds in the following cycling
competitions, but he admitted that China is the main rival for
Japan especially in women's events.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team leader Li Xin said that the Chinese male
cyclists, including Li and fourth-placed Ma, were not as
experienced as their Japanese rivals.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, the Chinese men's team has never beat the
Japanese in Asian Tournaments," he said, "Though we are becoming
stronger, we have to admit that there is still a gap between us."
</P>
<P>
Thailand has surprised the participating teams with its
extraoridnary good performances. Gen. Youthana Kumdee, president
of the Thai Amateur Cycling Association, was "very happy" about
it.
</P>
<P>
With the gold medal won by Thai Phannaro Kongsamut in Monday's
Down Hill competition and the silver and bronze Tuesday, Kumdee
said he had every reason to believe that cycling in Thailand will
have a brighter future with "more sponsors coming to support the
sport". 
</P>
</TEXT>
