<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Strategy, Open-Door Policy High on NATO Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The revision of NATO strategy
and maintaining its open-door policy will be the main items on the
agenda of next April's Washington summit of the western military
alliance.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said after Tuesday's NATO
foreign ministers council meeting that the meeting was as a
tune-up for the summit set to celebrate the alliance's 50th
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers tasked the NATO council of permanent
representatives, the alliance's day-to-day decision-making body,
with preparing the final text of the strategic concept for
approval at the summit.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the new strategic concept must be "fully
consistent with the alliance's new security environment" and
should reaffirm NATO's commitment to collective defense and the
transatlantic link.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued after the council meeting said that the new
strategic concept should commit NATO to be ready with a full range
of capabilities to enhance security and stability in the
Euro-Atlantic area in the next century and to implement
non-Article V crisis response operations outside the NATO
geographical area.
</P>
<P>
Article V of NATO's Washington Treaty entitles the alliance to
self-defense in line with the spirit of the United Nations Charter.
</P>
<P>
NATO has invited Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic to join
it while more central and eastern European countries aspire to
join the alliance.
</P>
<P>
The NATO secretary-general stressed the alliance would keep its
door open to other applicant countries, but NATO observers believe
that it is unlikely to issue invitations at the Washington summit
for more countries to start another round of enlargement.
</P>
<P>
A senior NATO official told the press last Friday that the
alliance was considering initiatives to make some of the applicant
countries for NATO membership feel more secure in their
preparation for accession.
</P>
<P>
But the official declined to elaborate on the details of the
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
Countries that are believed to have a better chance for what
NATO is considering as binding promises include Slovenia, Romania
and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia and the Baltic countries of Latvia, Estonia and
Lithuania are also applying for NATO membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
