<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Harvests Gold in Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Takashi Yamamoto broke the
Asian record in the men's 100m butterfly to start Japan's sweep of
four swimming golds out of five at the Asian Games on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chinese swimmers had to swallow the bitterness after they only
managed five silvers.
</P>
<P>
Yamamoto clocked 53.34 seconds to eclipse the old Asian mark
of 53.97, set by Chinese swimmer Xiong Guoming in the Hiroshima
Asian Games four years ago.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Japanese was followed by Zhang Xiao of China in
54.40. Han Kyu-Chui of South Korea came third in 54.83.
</P>
<P>
Yamamoto was not satisfied with his performance. "I tried to
beat my personal best of 52.88, but in vain. It's a little
disappointing."
</P>
<P>
"It is a certainty for me to win here since nobody can match me
in Asia," said Kinki University student. "My goal is to win in
Olympics and world championships."
</P>
<P>
Tsai Shu-Min ruined the otherwise perfect day for Japan as she
snatched the first-ever Asian Games swimming gold for Chinese
Teipei over 48 years.
</P>
<P>
She touched home first in 2:00.89 in the women's 200m freestyle
final, beating China's 16-year-old prodigy Qin Caini into second
place. Japanese Sachiko Yamada was third.
</P>
<P>
"The gold is a windfall to me. I had no confidence of winning
before the competition," said the 18-year-old Tsai.
</P>
<P>
"Now I will try my best to win more golds for Chinese Taipei,"
added Tsai, who will enter 400m freestyle, 4x100m freestyle,
4x200m freestyle and 4x100m medlay relay.
</P>
<P>
Takahiro Mori put Japan back onto the winning track when he
timed 4:20.98 to claim the men's 400m individual medley.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old Japanese was followed by Chinese veteran
swimmer Xiong Guoming, who clocked 4:22.57. Ratapong Sirisanont
of Thailand came in third in 4:24.15.
</P>
<P>
Mori felt a lot of drive to win the gold. "Our swimming
officials held a meeting with us last night, and we decided to
beat China in the pool," he said. "That decision gave me energy
and motivation."
</P>
<P>
"Chinese young swimmers performed very well," said Mori, "But
our young generation are also fully fledged. It is the younger
generation that will make difference in the Olympics or world
champioships."
</P>
<P>
Japanese Masami Tanaka, the 19-year-old high school student,
snatched the women's 200m breaststroke title in 2:28.44, beating
Chinese Qi Hui into second spot.
</P>
<P>
"Although I was a little tired, I was full of confidence,"
Tanaka said. "The win will help boost my confidence in the later
events."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese swimmers denied China's last chance for gold in
the men's 4x200m freestyle relay, in which they triumphed in
7:30.53.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese timed 7:34.11 for silver and the South Koreans
got the bronze.
</P>
<P>
"Just as expected, today is the darkest day for Chinese
swimmers," said Chinese head coach Zhang Xiong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
