<HEADLINE> Chinese Exhibition on Ethnic Groups' Education Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- A National Ethnic Textbook
Exhibition opened in Beijing today, with textbooks in 30 ethnic
group languages used by primary and middle school students on
display.
</P>
<P>
Xia Zhu, director of the Education Ministry's Ethnic Education
Bureau, said at the opening, "I was the son of poor Tibetans, and
lost my parents and became orphaned at the age of 7. It was the
government that helped me complete my college education. I used
the Tibetan language all through my schooling and Chinese in my
daily life."
</P>
<P>
China has introduced a bilingual education system and more than
10,000 schools use both ethnic languages and Chinese for teaching
some 6 million students. China publishes more than 3,500 textbooks
of various kinds in 30 languages for 21 ethnic minority groups,
with 100 million volumes, annually.
</P>
<P>
Xia says that China's Constitution and other laws state clearly
that there is equality and freedom in the use of ethnic
languages. The Central Government this year plans to add 2.2
billion yuan (265 million US dollars) to ethnic groups' education
to make it obligatory in ethnic regions.
</P>
<P>
Xia says that being located in economic backward areas make
ethnic groups' education costly and difficult and there are
still problems that need to be tackled.
</P>
<P>
There are 53 of China's 55 national minorities that use more
than 80 languages, including nearly 30 written ones. The Hui and
the Man have used the Han or Chinese language for a long time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
