<HEADLINE> Air India Sustains Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Air India, the government air
fleet, sustained a loss of 1.29 billion rupees (30.73 million U.S.
dollars) in the first half of the current financial year beginning
from April 1, Civil Aviation Minister Kumar said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a written reply to Rajya Sabha, the Upper House of Indian
Parliament which has been in session since Monday, Ananth Kumar
cited increased expenditure and reduction in yield as main reasons
for the loss.
</P>
<P>
Other reasons the minister listed for the loss were rising
interests costs, increased competition and operational costs, rise
in wage bill and other staff costs, depreciation in rupee value
and spurting landing, handling and navigational charges.
</P>
<P>
Air India, mainly on international flights, had accumulated a
loss of 1.81 billion rupees (47.6 million dollars) in the
financial year of 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
Kumar said that a committee of experts has been set up under
his ministry to comprehensively examine the reasons for the loss
and suggest strategies to turn around the corporation.
</P>
<P>
Air India and India Airlines, which is mainly on domestic
flights, have accepted suggestions by the international
consultancy firm A F Ferguson &AMP; Co's for a merger of the two
corporations in a three-year time frame.
</P>
<P>
The joint board of directors of the two airlines decided Monday
to implement the merger in a phased manner beginning with the
merger of various departments such as operations and engineering
of both airlines.
</P>
<P>
A report by Ferguson recommended a two-tier structure
consisting of a holding company and a joint management group.
</P>
</TEXT>
