<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Ministry On European Veterinary Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Zhu Bangzao said today that China hopes that the
European Union will deal properly with matters raised in its
veterinary report on China, for the healthy development of
Sino-European relations.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the question that the EU might continue its
import restrictions on Chinese poultry, Zhu said, China has
taken note of the EU report in September on China's animal
epidemic prevention and quarantine system and quality guarantee
system. It exaggerates the problems without referring to
specific cases, and its purpose is to maintain restrictions of
poultry and meat imports from China, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
For the past two years, China has had a cooperative attitude
towards EU legislation, he said. In keeping with EU regional
management requirements, China has selected the city of Shanghai
and Shandong and Jilin provinces as key areas and has spent
hundreds of millions of yuan improving local enterprises, local
systems, and solving problems discovered by the EU's inspections.
</P>
<P>
The report reflects the EU's intention to hinder normal trade
through technical barriers, Zhu said, adding that it infringes on
the interests of Chinese enterprises and on those of European
customers, and will have a negative impact on the development of
trade and economic relations between China and the EU.  
</P>
</TEXT>
