<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection Official on Coastal Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Zhu Guangyao, deputy-director
of China's Environmental Protection Administration, has said that
there is a serious pollution problem in the country's coastal
waters.
</P>
<P>
He says that, even though an effort has been made to protect
the coastal environment over the past decade, the amount of
pollution continues to expand and the water quality to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
Major pollutants include inorganic nitrogen and phosphorus,
organic pollutants, and oil. Recent studies show inorganic
nitrogen and phosphorus in the Bohai Bay, Yellow Sea, East China
Sea and South China Sea well beyond state standards.
</P>
<P>
Zhu says that land is still being reclaimed from the sea at
will in some regions, damaging coral reefs and mangrove swamps,
and resulting in serious marine ecological problems.
</P>
<P>
Coral reefs have decreased from 50,000 hectares in the 1950s to
15,000 hectares and the amount of coastal wetlands has been
reduced by a million hectares, nearly half of the country's total
coastal wetlands. The damage to forests in some coastal areas is
also very serious.
</P>
<P>
This has decreased biodiversity and increased marine disasters,
Zhu says, and urban waste water has become an important source of
pollution along the coast.
</P>
<P>
China is striving to focus efforts on combating pollution in
the Bohai Bay, which has serious problems, so as to advance
off-shore environmental protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
