<HEADLINE> Mongolia's Day in Judo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia made an impact in the
Asian Games judo competitions when Erdenet-Od H. and Boldbaatar
Haliun won two gold medals for the world's biggest inner-land
country on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Boldbaatar, a father of one, stunned reigning world champion
Nakamura Kenzo of Japan in the men's 73-kilogram category to take
the gold.
</P>
<P>
Nakamura, also gold medalist at the Atlanta Olympic Games in
1996, looked in top form but the 27-year-old Boldbaatar was
stronger.
</P>
<P>
"I met him three times and lost all of them," Boldbaatar said.
"I told me I must win the fourth."
</P>
<P>
Boldbaatar, who won a bronze in Hiroshima four years ago, said
that he felt no pressure before the Olympic champion.
</P>
<P>
"We are very familiar with each other's techniques, and I only
wanted to use all my strength and try my best," he said.
</P>
<P>
The third place in the 73kg went to Uzbekistan's Andrey
Shturbabin and South Korea's Kim Dae-Wook.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia's first gold was won by Erdenet-Od in the women's 57kg
class when she edged Chinese Shen Jun with a unanimous decision
from three referees. Neither of them could score after the five
minutes competition.
</P>
<P>
The day was also a disaster for twice world chamion and Olympic
bronze medalist Jung Sung-Sook of South Korea, who suffered a
surprise defeat to the 21-year-old Chinese Shen in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
Shen was shocked by the referee's decision and said it was
unfair to her.
</P>
<P>
"When I stood on the mat waiting for the referee's decesion, I
belived I must be ruled the winner, because I had an andvantage in
the match," she said.
</P>
<P>
But Liu Wugong, coach of the Chinese national team, said Shen
deserved the silver.
</P>
<P>
"The Mongolian enjoyed an edge over Shen," Liu said. "She
should not complain about that."
</P>
<P>
Jung and Kusakabe Kie of Japan finished joint third in the
category.
</P>
<P>
The women's 52kg final was an affair between South Korea and
DPR Korea.
</P>
<P>
Kye Sung-Hui of DPR Korea, gold medalist in the 48kg at the
Atlanta Olympic Games, proved too much for Kim Hye-Sook of South
Korea, who won the event in last year's world championships in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
China's Li Ying, who fell in the first round to Kim Hye-Sook,
won all the other matches and wound up for bronze medal, which was
shared by Japan's Nagai Kazue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
