<HEADLINE> Indonesian Former Minister Questioned on Car Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian former industry and
trade minister Tunky Ariwibowo Tuesday came to the Attorney
General's Office to be questioned over the Timor national car
project.
</P>
<P>
The Attorney General's Office also questioned Hadiyanto,
treasurer of the Dharmais Foundation, one of the seven foundations
handed over to the government by former president Soeharto last
month.
</P>
<P>
Hadiyanto arrived an hour later after Ariwibowo, who had served
as minister in two Soeharto cabinets, and the questioning was held
in the main building.
</P>
<P>
Their appearance at the Attorney General's Office set the stage
for Wednesday's much anticipated questioning of Soeharto himself.
</P>
<P>
The Timor national car project, which received special tax
privileges from the Soeharto administration, was developed by
Soeharto's youngest son Hutomo "Tommy" Mandala Putra.
</P>
<P>
Timor was the sole recipient of an import duty and luxury tax
exemption from late 1996 to January 1998 when the International
Monetary Fund insisted Indonesia stop the preferential treatment.
The tax exemption made the car 60 percent cheaper than its
counterparts on the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Andi M. Ghalib described the project as a
graft-infested project designed entirely for self-profit.
</P>
<P>
"The national car program stipulated in Presidential Decree No.
42/1996 was a program of nepotism because it was designed solely
to profit the family," Ghalib said.
</P>
<P>
The project had caused the country losses of 1.55 billion U.S.
dollars, Ghalib said in a statement distributed to members of the
House of Representatives Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said the issuance of the presidential decree on the project
and regulations backing the project were made possible merely
through collusion between Hutomo and related government officials.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
