<HEADLINE> UAE Ready to Talk with Iran over Islands: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan has informed Iran that the United Arab Emirates (UAE) is
ready to resume talks with it over the three disputed islands in
the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan
Al-Nahyan in Abu Dhabi, Annan talked with Iranian
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi on phone Monday night to inform
him of the emirates' readiness.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by Iranian Foreign Ministry Tuesday said
the U.N. chief told Kharrazi that Zayed voiced his country's
desire to resume bilateral talks with Iran at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Kharrazi said that "as we have announced time and
again, we welcome visits by UAE officials to Iran to hold
bilateral negotiations and to eliminate misunderstandings between
the two countries."
</P>
<P>
And there are areas of common interests and cooperation between
Iran and the UAE, he added.
</P>
<P>
Annan is in Abu Dhabi to attend the summit of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) that opened Monday. The GCC groups
Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the UAE.
</P>
<P>
Iran took over the three islands of Abu Musa, the Greater and
the Lesser Tunbs at the mouth of the strategically important
Strait of Hormuz in 1971 after British forces withdrew from the
region.
</P>
<P>
However, the islands were claimed by both Tehran and Abu
Dhabi. Their diplomatic relations were lowered to the level of
charge d'affaires in 1992 after the UAE lodged a protest against
Iran's full control on the islands.
</P>
<P>
Iran has since been insisting on solving its
"misunderstandings" with the UAE through bilateral talks, while
Abu Dhabi called for an international arbitration of the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
