<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Government Adopts Wiretapping Amendment Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government
Tuesday approved an amendment bill to protect secrecy in
communications and restrict wiretapping by police and security
agencies.
</P>
<P>
Under the revised bill, investigators will be required to cease
wiretapping if they fail to receive court approval within 36 hours.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the amendment demands that in case of emergency, the
law enforcement authorities have to inform the court of whom they
have wiretapped, for what reason, and for what period before
obtaining court approval.
</P>
<P>
The range of crimes in which wiretapping is permitted would be
also reduced. Furthermore, those who are found to have engaged in
illegal wiretapping or to have revealed illegally wiretapped
conversations would be subject to up to 10 years imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Wiretapping by the government became a hot issue after the
opposition Grand National Party accused the government in the
National Assembly's audit and inspection of state-run Korea
Telecom in October of having illegally tapped opposition members.
</P>
<P>
In a recent joint statement, the ministers of justice, defense
and the head of the national intelligence agency promised to
revise the law in order to prevent law-enforcement authorities
from abusing wiretapping.
</P>
<P>
The amendment is expected to pass the National Assembly, or
parliament, during its current session, which ends on December 18
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
