<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Xinhua HK Branch Serves as Bridge Between </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Xinhua News Agency Hong
Kong Branch has been playing an increasingly important role in
promoting the communication and cooperation between Hong Kong and
the mainland since Hong Kong returned to China on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The branch, an institution authorized by the Central People's
Government of China in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR), has served as a bridge between the mainland and the SAR
under the "one country, two systems" policy.
</P>
<P>
During the one and half year after the Chinese government
resumed its exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong, which had been
under the British rule for over 150 years, the Xinhua Hong Kong
Branch has helped 1,600 groups or 30,000 of Hong Kong people to
visit the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 1,100 groups or 15,000 people from the mainland have
visited the SAR with the assistance of the branch.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Xinhua branch has been working for the promotion
of the exchanges and cooperation between Hong Kong and the
mainland ever since it was established 51 years ago.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return to China, more and more Hong Kong
people from various walks of life expressed their eagerness to
enhance their understanding of the motherland and to exchange and
cooperate with people in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the obstacles to the exchange and cooperation
between the mainland and Hong Kong caused by the British rule have
been gradually removed after Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
Under these circumstances, there are more exchanges and
cooperation between the two sides in the economic, social and
cultural fields after July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In July this year, 26 students from eight universities and
colleges in Hong Kong went to Tibet, a mysterious place in their
minds, with the Xinhua branch helping them contact departments
concerned in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
During their 9-day stay in Tibet, these students toured the
beautiful highland of the southwestern autonomous region of China
and visited some Tibetan people.
</P>
<P>
They found a true story of Tibet which is totally different
from what they learned from the Western media. They said that
their trip was very fruitful and thanked the Xinhua branch for
erecting a bridge for them to Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, more and more people have come to Hong Kong
from the mainland with the help of the Xinhua branch. They not
only saw the great vigor of Hong Kong under the concept of "one
country, two systems" after its return to China but also realized
that Hong Kong still plays a unreplaceable role in China's opening
to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, with the help of the Xinhua branch and other
institutions, organizations and foundations in Hong Kong, a large
number of people from the mainland have learned advanced knowledge
and expertise in the fields of law, accounting, medicine and
management from Hong Kong and this has helped a lot in China's
modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
In the course of contacting people from various walks of life
in Hong Kong, the Xinhua Hong Kong Branch has continuously
conveyed the opinions and suggestions from the Hong Kong people to
government departments in China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
In June this year, the branch and the Chinese General Chamber
of Commerce of Hong Kong collected views among local business
people on the investment environment of the mainland, with a view
to helping the mainland improve the investment environment.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Enzhu, director of the Xinhua Hong Kong Branch, said that
Xinhua will, as always, act strictly under the policy of "one
country, two systems" and do its utmost to promote the exchange
and cooperation between Hong Kong and the mainland, playing a
better role as a bridge for the economic development and common
progress of the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Land Grants Accord for HK Container Terminal 9 Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government
signed a land grants agreement for the construction of Container
Terminal 9 (CT9) with three joint developers here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
These include Asia Container Terminals, Modern Terminals
Limited, and Hong Kong International Terminals. They will invest
over 10 billion HK dollars (1.28 billion U.S. dollars) in the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement on CT9 is a clear demonstration of their
commitment to Hong Kong and their confidence in the long term
prospect of our container port and economy," said Patrick Lau,
Acting Secretary for Planning, Environment and Lands, at the
signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Now, there are eight container terminals at Kwai Chung and on
Stonecutters Island which are privately owned and operated, with a
total of 19 berths for ocean-going vessels.
</P>
<P>
The new terminal will have six berths and a design capacity of
handling 2.6 million twenty-foot equivalent units (TEUs) of
containers a year.
</P>
<P>
Together with the facilities at Kwai Chung, the new terminal
will be able to cope with forecast growth in demand of the Hong
Kong Container Port until the early 2000s.
</P>
<P>
Construction work will begin in mid-1999. The first berth of
the new terminal is expected to come into operation in 2002 and
the remaining berths at five or six months intervals thereafter.
</P>
</TEXT>
