<HEADLINE> Marcos Family Given 1 Year to Decide on Compromise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said here Tuesday that he gives the Marcos family one year
to decide on compromise talks with his government to settle the
tug-of-war over the family's alleged ill-gotten wealth.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with reporters, Estrada said his administration
is willing to negotiate with Imelda Marcos on the disposition of
her family's alleged ill-gotten wealth as long as the process will
speed up the recovery of the assets, prove advantageous to the
government and hasten the use of the money for pro-poor projects.
</P>
<P>
"We've waited more than 12 years, so we can wait about one
year," he said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said his economic advisers have determined that the
negotiations will speed up the recovery process.
</P>
<P>
"It has already taken 12 years, and nothing has happened so we
might try through negotiations so it will be faster and at least
we can get hold of the money and spend it on the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Imelda has rejected the proposed compromise talks and has
announced plans to file a 500 billion peso (12.5 billion U.S.
dollars) suit against the alleged cronies of her late husband,
former president Ferdinand Marcos.
</P>
<P>
Imelda claimed that her husband entrusted these properties to
his cronies at the height of his power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
