<HEADLINE> France Opposes U.S. Proposals on NATO Function </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- France has expressed opposition
to wide-ranging U.S. proposals to allow unilateral action by NATO
and warned against division of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said at the NATO foreign
ministers' meeting which started in Brussels on Tuesday that
"collective defense" should remain the foundation of NATO.
</P>
<P>
He rejected U.S. proposals that NATO assume responsibility in
controlling the proliferation of arms of mass destruction, and
that the alliance take action in times of crisis without the
mandate of the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said the proliferation of arms of mass destruction is
one of the risks faced by the NATO, but not the only one.
</P>
<P>
He also said NATO should not be the only "player" in
controlling that problem, but "one player among others".
</P>
<P>
As for the proposal of how to deal with crises, Vedrine said it
was not "justified" that NATO should look for "a new federal-style
concept" on that subject.
</P>
<P>
"There, we could run the risk of thinning down the alliance and
dividing the allies," he said, stressing that all missions
involving the deployment of troops should be approved by the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The NATO foreign ministers' meeting in Brussels was held in
preparation for the Washington summit of the alliance scheduled
for next spring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
