<HEADLINE> NATO Authorizes Extraction Force Operation in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- NATO foreign ministers on
Tuesday authorized the operation of the extraction force as the
back-up for the international truce verifiers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers, meeting in their year-end council,
authorized an activation order for the NATO-led force, codenamed
Operation Joint Guarantor, of which the first troops had already
arrived in Macedonia over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
NATO will rapidly deploy the 1,700-strong extraction force in
Macedonia to provide the ability to withdraw Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) verifiers in an
emergency, the alliance said.
</P>
<P>
The western military alliance urged both the Yugoslav
authorities and the leaders of the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo to
maintain "scrupulously" the ceasefire and comply fully with the
United Nations Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"We remain firmly convinced that the problems of Kosovo can
only be resolved through a process of open and unconditional
dialogue between the authorities in Belgrade and representatives
of the Kosovar leadership," said a statement issued from the
council meeting.
</P>
<P>
The NATO-led extraction force, which was formed at the request
of the OSCE, consists of troops from France, Britain, Germany,
Italy, the Netherlands and Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Macedonia-based special force was designed to react within
30 to 60 minutes if weather permits to pull out the international
verifiers from Kosovo or to rescue of verifiers taken hostage.
</P>
<P>
In a deal reached between Yugoslavia and the OSCE, it is the
responsibility of the Yugoslav authorities to guarantee the safety
of the 2,000-member verification mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
