<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Poses Threat to School Life in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The fast spread of HIV/AIDS
has posed great threat to the education system in Kenya, a senior
official with the U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Latest data show that "22 percent of girls between the ages of
15 and 19 are HIV positive, whereas four percent of boys in the
same age group are HIV positive" in Kenya, according to Chrispin
Wilson, chief of UNICEF's Kenya Office.
</P>
<P>
"It is now undeniable that the entire education system of this
country is under threat of HIV/AIDS," he said at the launching
ceremony of the 1999 State of the World's Children report here.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeing a child whose very life is threatened since he
or she has no access to the vital information needed about
protection against HIV/AIDS, and little chance to develop the
life skills that can help to ensure their survival in the age of
AIDS," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
In the worst affected provinces of Kenya, he said, teachers
are dying of AIDS with alarming frequency, leaving school-rooms
in towns and villages without anyone to instruct the pupils.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of children in the east African country have been
orphaned by the fatal disease and thus denied access to basic
education, and their number is "rapidly increasing," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chrispin called for more efforts on the part of the Kenyan
government to give priority to anti-AIDS education in schools
countrywide.
</P>
<P>
At the same function, Kenyan Education Minister Kalonzo
Musyoka said the gross enrollment rate of the country's primary
school rose to 84 percent in 1998 from 76 percent in 1996, but
still far below 95 percent in 1989.
</P>
<P>
"I hope this (trend) continues as we work toward achieving
universal primary education by 2010," said Musyoka.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are about six million pupils in about 17,000
primary schools in Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
