<HEADLINE> Manila Sets Conditions on "Bridge Financing" for PAL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
Tuesday set four conditions for a possible "bridge-financing" plan
to keep Philippine Airlines (PAL) on air, a move that would tap
private banks and "strategic partners" in PAL's rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
At his regular press briefing here, Presidential spokesperson
Jerry Barican said that private banks and government financing
institutions would provide loans to PAL only after certain
conditions are met.
</P>
<P>
"The government's policy remains unchanged. There will be no
government bailout or subsidy to PAL," Barican said.
</P>
<P>
Barican said the implementation of the bridge-financing scheme
must meet the following conditions:
</P>
<P>
-- PAL's continued operation is commercially viable.
</P>
<P>
-- PAL will be subjected to the usual credit evaluation.
</P>
<P>
-- The financing package will involve a consortium of private
banks and strategic partners.
</P>
<P>
-- This package will form part of a rehabilitation plan
approved by PAL creditors and the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview Tuesday morning, Finance Secretary Edgardo
Espiritu stressed that any financing plan for PAL involving
government financial institutions and private banks would have to
be in the form of loans.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said PAL can borrow from these commercial institutions
while waiting for fresh investments to be infused into the
airline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
