<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Seeks to Increase Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is seeking ways to
increase next year's exports to about 10 billion U.S. dollars, the
Vietnam News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The target was set by the Ministry of Trade in an import-export
plan submitted to the prime minister for approval, the
English-language daily said.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, agriculture, forestry and marine products will
account for 37 percent of the total export, and light industrial
and handicraft products over 38 percent. The goal for heavy
industries is set at more than 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve these goals, the ministry plans to expand
export markets with focus put on markets in the Commonwealth of
Independent States, Eastern Europe, the European Union, China and
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
This year, Vietnam's total export value is estimated at 9.3
billion dollars, up 0.3 percent from last year, but the growth is
far behind the expected increase of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese authorities blamed the regional crisis for decreased
buying power in the major importers of Vietnamese products.
</P>
<P>
Devalued regional currencies have also hurt the competitiveness
of Vietnamese goods, especially textiles, garments, rubber, shoes
and marine products that are also exported by other countries of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese officials admitted that the low competitiveness of
Vietnamese products and heavy dependence on Asian markets also had
negative effects on Vietnam's exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
