<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Let Foreigners Observe General Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Foreign observers will have the
chance to monitor Indonesia's general election on June 7, 1999,
Abu Hasan Sadzili, chairman of the special committee on the 1999
general election, told reporters here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible for them (foreign observers) to come to
Indonesia and observe the election," Sadzili said.
</P>
<P>
He said many international organizations have approached him,
asking if they could observe the election, the first to be held
since former president Soeharto resigned from office following
massive rioting in the country in May this year.
</P>
<P>
"Many people have expressed their enthusiasm -- usually from
the United States and European countries. Even the United Nations
will send a team," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sadzili said his committee has also asked local groups, such as
the Independent Committee of Election Observers and universities,
to join in the monitoring of the election.
</P>
<P>
They will be supervised by the Supreme Court, he said, adding
that their observations will be passed on to the committee on
election monitoring which will review them.
</P>
<P>
"If it sees any dishonesty, the committee will follow it up
with the court," Sadzili added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian President B.J. Habibie has said his government will
invite observers from the United Nations Development Program, the
United States, Germany, France, Japan and Australia to see for
themselves if Indonesia's general election is held democratically.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
