<HEADLINE> At Least 18 People Killed in Somali Faction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 8 (Xinhua) -- At least 18 people were
killed and more than 32 others, mainly civilians, wounded in a
fierce fighting between tow factions in Baidoa Town in southern
Somalia, reliable sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The fighting between Rahanwein Resistance Army (RRA) and those
of faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid Monday night was the
worst armed clash ever in the important town, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of kiosks and poorly-built residential houses were
similarly destroyed by the heavy shelling from both sides in the
fight for control of Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
RRA spokesman Mohamed Ali Aden Qalinle told reporters in
Mogadishu Tuesday through VHF radio that his forces have killed
ten of Aidid's men and destroyed five battle wagons during the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
But a spokesman for Aidid's men in the field said Tuesday that
they had lost six of their fighters while 14 others have been
wounded.
</P>
<P>
The militia spokesman claimed that Aidid's men had the upper
hand in the fighting, saying the RRA had left 25 dead in the
town.
</P>
<P>
The latest reports from Baidoa indicated Tuesday that it is
calm but tense in the town under the control of Aidid's forces.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that the forces of Aidid are still chasing
pockets of retreating RRA men at the outskirts of the town while
the bewildered civilians are checking what is left of their
houses and business stalls for possible restart of normal life.
</P>
</TEXT>
