<HEADLINE> China Regrets Over EU Report on Quarantine System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- China has expressed regret over
the European Union's critical report on the country's quarantine
system and the proposal to continue an import ban on China's
poultry, insisting the problems were exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
Hu Chusheng, spokesman of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), said that the report was written
after an EU veterinary inspection to China last September and
"fully demonstrates the EU's true intention of obstructing normal
trade by the use of technical barriers."
</P>
<P>
He went on, "It will harm not only the economic interests of
relevant companies in China, but also the interests of consumers
in EU nations, thus bringing a negative influence on the further
growth of Sino-EU economic and trade relations."
</P>
<P>
The European Union recently published the new report on China's
methods for preventing animal epidemics, quarantine and quality
guarantee systems and related processing plants.
</P>
<P>
Hu said it exaggerated problems without referring to specific
cases.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that over the past two years since the import ban
was imposed, China has been careful to respect and cooperate with
certain EU regulations.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account the relevant EU laws, China took specific
action to rectify any problems following previous inspections,
particularly in Shanghai, Shandong and Jilin, which have the
highest livestock raising levels in the country, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
"It is the hope of the Chinese Government that the EU will
consider the general interest of Sino-EU relations and handle this
issue properly in order to clear obstacles for a healthy
development in those relations," Hu concluded.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
