<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Announces Candidates for Local Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Seven recognized political
parties and four independent groups are entitled to take part in
the election to the North Western Provincial Council (NWPC),
Commissioner of Elections Dayananda Dissanayake announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The elections commissioner said there are 446 candidates
contesting 52 seats including two bonus seats for the NWPC, which
comprises the two districts of Kurunegala and Puttalam.
</P>
<P>
However, the exact date of the election is yet to be announced
by the Commission of Elections.
</P>
<P>
Six parties and one independent group will compete in the
election in Kurunegala District while seven parties and three
independent groups will contest in Pattalam District.
</P>
<P>
The contenders in Kurunegala District include the main
opposition United National Party, Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna
(People's Liberation Front), the New Left Front, the ruling
People's Alliance, the Muslim United Liberation Front, the Liberal
Party and an independent group led by H.D.P. Hemanthanie.
</P>
<P>
The contenders in Pattalam District include Sri Lanka
Progressive Front and the above-mentioned six parties as well as
three independent groups led respectively by N.K. Amarasena,
M.I.M. Halith, and H. Ratnapala.
</P>
<P>
Following the dissolution of the provincial council in
November, the elections commissioner had called for nomination of
candidates from December 1 to 8.
</P>
<P>
Nomination closed at 12:00 Tuesday. During the
seven-and-a-half-day period, the two nomination centers in the two
districts received a total of 19 party or group nomination papers,
of which two were rejected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
