<HEADLINE> 130 Million Children in Dire Need of Education: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- More than 130 million children
of primary school age in developing countries are growing up
without access to basic education, according to a U.N. report
released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 State of the World's Children report said that girls
are the most affected, with 73 million of them lacking access to
primary school education.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly a billion people, two thirds of them women, will enter
the 21st century unable to read a book or sign their names --
much less operate a computer or understand a simple application
form," said the report from the U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
"They will live, as now, in more desperate poverty and poorer
health than most of those who can. They are the world's
functional illiterates and their numbers are growing," it added.
</P>
<P>
The report urged governments worldwide to work in partnership
with multiple sectors of the society in order to have a better
chance of achieving the goal of education for all.
</P>
<P>
The report also called for an expansion of the education
revolution throughout the world which emphasizes access to high
quality learning and a child-right centered approach.
</P>
<P>
It cited child centered learning, curriculum relevance,
lessons conducted in local languages and proximity of schools to
homes as some of the factors that can enhance the quality of the
school experience for all children.
</P>
<P>
Others are security, supply of safe drinking water and
latrines and rooting out gender bias from textbooks and
materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
