<HEADLINE> S.Korean President Decides Not to Sack Defense Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 8 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung on Tuesday voiced his decision not to sack his Defense
Minister Chun Yong-taek blamed responsible for recent military
accidents, despite mounting pressures from the public and the
opposition Grand National Party (GNP).
</P>
<P>
However, President Kim issued a "stern warning" to the minister
and urged military leaders to ensure there will be no more
accidents in military camps, presidential spokesman Park Jie-won
said.
</P>
<P>
The president has once considered replacing the minister, but
decided not to do so because of Chun's contributions to military
reforms and successful management of defense affairs, Park said.
</P>
<P>
"The president also noted that military accidents actually
decreased by 37 percent this year and that no defense minister has
ever been dismissed for an accident," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chun Yong-taek said on Monday that he would step down
voluntarily if another accident were to occur.
</P>
<P>
In the past four weeks, 11 South Korean soldiers were killed by
tanks, explosions and car crashes.
</P>
<P>
In an unprecedented accidents, an air force anti-aircraft
missile accidentally launched last Friday wounded three people,
scaring the whole nation.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a GNP spokesman said the defense minister must be
replaced as the accidents were the results of lax discipline and
the rock-bottom state of morale.
</P>
<P>
The opposition attributed the lax military discipline and lower
morale to President Kim's engagement policy toward the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
