<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Spokesman on President Jiang's Visit to Japan (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
recent visit to Japan has achieved important results and apart
from summarizing the past and looking to the future it will be
conducive to promoting the growth of Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Zhu Bangzao made these remarks
here this afternoon at a routine press conference when asked to
comment on the visit, the first state visit to Japan by a Chinese
head of state.
</P>
<P>
He said it also took place at an important time in history with
the imminent approach of a new century.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, President Jiang and Japanese Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi, while taking into consideration the past, exchanged
views on the future development of bilateral relations and
international issues of common concern and reached important
consensus, said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
A joint declaration was also issued, added Zhu, pointing out
that this is the third significant document aimed at guiding the
development of bilateral ties following the Sino-Japanese Joint
Statement and the Sino-Japanese Treaty of Peace and Friendship.
</P>
<P>
Zhu quoted the declaration which stated that facing up to the
past and correctly evaluating history are important basis for the
development of bilateral relations. The Japanese side admitted its
aggression against China for the first time, and expressed again a
deep introspection and apology for the grave suffering of the
Chinese people caused by that war of aggression.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese side had reiterated that it will abide strictly by
the principles concerning the Taiwan issue enshrined in the
Sino-Japanese Joint Statement, will stress that there is only one
China, and that Japan will never support Taiwan's independence,
has no ambitions itself in Taiwan and will restrict activities
with Taiwan to non-official and regional contacts, he added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Zhu stated, both the historical and Taiwan issues
constitute the main principles in Sino-Japanese relations, and a
correct understanding and treatment of the aggression against
China launched by Japanese militarists linked to a proper handling
of the Taiwan issue form an important political basis for
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side hopes that the Japanese side will keep its
commitment and promote a new process of bilateral exchanges and
cooperation in various fields, in accordance with the principles
defined in the bilateral joint statement and treaty of peace and
friendship, Zhu noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
