<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Opposes Dalai Lama's Splittist Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- China firmly opposes any plans
by the Dalai Lama, under any circumstances, to visit foreign
countries to engage in political activities in a bid to split the
nation, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
China also objects to officials from other countries meeting
the Dalai Lama in any capacity or form, spokesman Zhu Bangzao
informed a routine press conference.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China noticed that France had invited the
Dalai Lama to attend celebrations marking the 50th anniversary of
the issuing of the International Declaration of Human Rights, and
to take part in a luncheon with the French President, Jacques
Chirac.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to express our deep concern and displeasure
about this and have made serious representation to the French
Government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu continued that it is common knowledge that the Dalai Lama
is not just an ordinary religious figure but a political exile who
has engaged in nefarious activities aimed at causing rifts in
China's national solidarity.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai Lama, who has relentlessly advocated the independence
of Tibet while still supposedly taking part in dialogue with the
Chinese central government, continues to travel the world on
propaganda campaigns to publicize globally the issue of Tibet, Zhu
said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, he has never once ceased these activities and is
therefore cheating, commented Zhu.
</P>
<P>
When he ruled Tibet, went on Zhu, he cruelly violated the basic
human rights of Tibetans, and therefore certainly does not qualify
to take part in activities to celebrate the human rights.
</P>
<P>
China has now demanded that France should consider the long
term, smooth and wide ranging Sino-French relations, and that to
prevent them from being damaged, France should not agree to the
Dalai Lama attending the above event, the lunch with President
Chirac or any official meetings, Zhu added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
