<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Overseas Business Bodies Urged to Help Domestic Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior trade official today
urged all China's official business organisations stationed
overseas to help domestic companies expand their export portfolios
and secure more foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Sun Zhenyu, vice-minister of China's Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation, outlined his suggestions to more than 200
commercial counselors, who operate in some 180 countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during the final day of a six day working conference
held in Beijing, he added that the counselors should provide
accurate and up to date commercial information from abroad for
China's domestic companies. He stressed that it doesn't matter
whether they are state-owned or private.
</P>
<P>
He included in the package such data as local laws on economic
cooperation and trade, market demand statistics, assessment of the
investment environment and the supply of relevant company analysis
reports.
</P>
<P>
Sun told the delegates that they should bear in mind the
need to help cultivate a new form of bilateral and multilateral
economic and trade relations between China and relevant countries
for the 21st century. "You must focus your attention on increasing
exports by every possible means and to help secure and make use of
overseas investment," he added.
</P>
<P>
An important aspect of their work, Sun said, was to make great
efforts to promote investment in China from major transnational
companies.
</P>
<P>
In order to help further boost China's export, the
counselors should also make major efforts to increase and
encourage the use of domestically produced materials for the
overseas processing sector, Sun said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
