<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Airport Enjoys Booming Business in 3 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Macao International Airport
has enjoyed marked growth in both passenger and cargo traffic
since it was officially inaugurated on December 8, 1995.
</P>
<P>
A simple ceremony was held at the departure hall of the airport
Tuesday morning to mark the third anniversary of its inauguration.
</P>
<P>
"After three years from the airport's inauguration, we can make
an objective assessment of this infrastructure's value to the
territory's development," said Joao Manuel de Sousa Moreira,
chairman of the board of directors of the Macao International
Airport Company.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Asian financial crisis has severely affected
airport activities worldwide. In Macao's case, it has caused the
flight suspension of two airlines from South Korea and one from
Malaysia. "Despite this negative scenario, we have maintained the
traffic growth."
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the airport handled 1.95 million passengers and 45,540
tons of goods, increasing 50 percent and 81.84 percent
respectively over 1996.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that passenger and cargo traffic this year
might reach 2.2 million persons and 64,000 tons of goods.
</P>
<P>
During the past three years, the airport has handled over 5.3
million passengers and 130,000 tons of cargo. It now serves 13
airline companies which operate 390 flights each week to 25
destinations around the world.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Macao has signed bilateral air service agreements
with 26 countries, and agreements with another eight countries
have been initialed.
</P>
<P>
With the competition of the large airports situated in Hong
Kong, Guangzhou, Shenzhen and Zhuhai, the Macao airport will have
to search for its own market and create appeal to the airlines
interested in flying to the region, the chairman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
