<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SFOR to Stay in Bosnia at Current Force Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- NATO foreign ministers agreed
on Tuesday that the NATO-led multinational SFOR will stay in
Bosnia at its current force level with the same mission.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, NATO decision-makers said that the
stabilization force will continue to assist and coordinate closely
with the United Nations and other international institutions such
as the International Police Task Force, the International War
Crimes Tribunal and the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation will continue to focus on the implementation of
the civil aspects of the Dayton peace accord that include the
return of refugees, reform and restructuring of local police, and
the building of democratic institutions in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
But NATO stressed that SFOR's presence cannot be maintained
indefinitely or its presence should reduce the responsibility of
the local authorities to ensure the stability of the Balkan
country.
</P>
<P>
The western military alliance said that it would continue to
support the efforts of the international community to help Bosnia
develop as a single, democratic and multi-ethnic state.
</P>
<P>
Elisabeth Rehn, a United Nations special envoy to Bosnia,
demanded in early November that SFOR remain in Bosnia for more
years.
</P>
<P>
She said that it would be difficult for the United Nations to
stay in Bosnia while others are leaving.
</P>
<P>
SFOR is the continuation of the NATO-led peace-making force of
IFOR that entered Bosnia after the Dayton peace accord was signed
in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
NATO has been considering reducing the SFOR force level or
replace it with a small-size deterrence force (DFOR) altogether.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
