<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Business Confidence Slightly Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 8 (Xinhua) -- A marginal increase in
South Africa's business confidence indicated that the depressed
mood of the past six months could be stabilizing, the South
African Chamber of Business (Sacob) has said.
</P>
<P>
The figures released by Sacob Monday showed that the business
confidence index increased to 84.8 in November from 84.4 in
October and September.
</P>
<P>
"Although the stabilization is still tentative and vulnerable
to further shocks, at least it ends the year on a more positive
note," the Business Day newspaper Tuesday quoted Sacob economic
policy director, Ben van Rensburg, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The strengthening of the Rand, a slight decline in the
consumer price index, rising share prices and better retail sales
were among the positive factors contributing to the rise, said
the paper.
</P>
<P>
On the down side, there was a deteriorating employment climate
in manufacturing, a lower gold price, a fall in export volumes
and a further decrease in new vehicle sales.
</P>
<P>
Sacob said next year should be seen as a year of
consolidation.
</P>
<P>
It forecast that the South African economy would grow by 1.5
percent next year compared with 0.2 percent projected for this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
