<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher on Renewed Interest in Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
rallied for the second consecutive session Tuesday as interest in
banking and telecommunications stocks led the general market
higher.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index ended the day 15.6 points firmer at
2771.7 points.
</P>
<P>
Yet while the all industrials index benefited from the interest
in banks, gaining 38.1 points to 4956.7, the resources sector
succumbed to continuing weak commodity prices, dropping 4.9 points
to 989.3.
</P>
<P>
"The market finished up in line with the firmer close on Wall
Street," Morgan Stockbroking's Simon Reed said.
</P>
<P>
"Interest continued to focus on banking and the
telecommunications sectors," Reed said.
</P>
<P>
The banking index stacked on 80.1 points to 6306.1 as
speculation about big bank mergers was again brought to the fore.
</P>
<P>
ANZ added 24.5 cents while Westpac gained 27 cents. Among the
other banks, NAB lifted 17 and the Commonwealth improved 18 cents.
</P>
<P>
In a recently typical move, Cable and Wireless Optus was the
most traded stock as interest in the telecommunications sector
continued unabated.
</P>
<P>
C&AMP;W Optus closed steady at 2.97 Australian dollars, with 15.76
million shares traded.
</P>
<P>
Telstra followed its competitor on the volume turnover table,
rising 11.2 cents with 10.48 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, weaker commodity prices took their
toll on an already dim outlook for the sector.
</P>
<P>
BHP dropped 10 cents and Rio Tinto slipped 19.3 cents while WMC
managed to lift six cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index gained 4.1 points to 1116.0 points with the
bullion price up 2.10 to 294.40 U.S. dollars per ounce.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 384.46 million stocks traded for 1.18
billion Australian dollars (719.8 million U.S. dollars), with
rising stocks outnumbering falling stocks 633 to 547 and 419
stocks steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
