<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Marginally Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
marginally stronger Tuesday, after languishing within a tight
range during the session amid sluggish pre-Christmas trade.
</P>
<P>
Arab Bank foreign exchange dealer Scott Young said there had
been good offers for the domestic currency in Europe Monday night
and that had been the only action of the past 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
The local unit finished here at 61.85 U.S. cents from 61.73 at
Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
During the day it traded between 61.73 and 62.03 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Overall the market was still looking at the Australian dollar
from a pessimistic point of view as commodities prices continued
to struggle, Young said.
</P>
<P>
The Commodity Research Bureau (CRB) Index closed weaker again
Monday night, down 0.24 to finish at 194.86.
</P>
<P>
The CRB is an index of 21 U.S. futures markets. It is not
weighted to Australia's exports and does not include coal, iron
ore and wool but traders follow it as an indicator for the
commodity price-sensitive Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Current commodities prices were bringing a "dark cloud" over
the Australian dollar, Young said.
</P>
<P>
Young said a strengthening U.S. dollar against the Japanese yen
Monday night may also have hindered the Australian dollar, but not
a lot.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, on the cross rates, the Australian dollar was buying
74.35 Japanese yen from 73.41 and 1.0386 German marks from 1.0355.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
