<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Observers Hail Conduct of Local Elections in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- International and local
observers have expressed satisfaction with the conduct of the
local government elections held in Nigeria last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of a report from a Commonwealth Secretariat team
which monitored the elections, Commonwealth Secretary-General
Chief Emeka Anyaoku said in a statement Monday that he was
delighted at the evident enthusiasm of the Nigerians during the
Saturday elections.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku pointed out that the massive turnout throughout the
country reflected the desire of the Nigerian people to achieve
the transition to democratic civilian rule in the west African
country.
</P>
<P>
He commended the Independent National Electoral Commission
(INEC) of Nigeria for working closely with the political parties
to facilitate an inclusive and transparent electoral process.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth has been engaged with the transition program
in the most populous African country by providing technical
assistance and experts to the INEC in the areas of logistics,
training and advice.
</P>
<P>
The 17-member Commonwealth observers team was present in
Nigeria for the Saturday's polls.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku said that the Commonwealth will send a similar team
for the state and federal elections in January and February next
year.
</P>
<P>
The Director of the African Division of the U.S.-based
International Republican Institute (IRI), Lloyd O. Pierson, said
in a statement issued Monday that the elections were peaceful,
voters were enthusiastic, and efforts were made to observe
electoral rules and procedures.
</P>
<P>
The IRI mission which arrived in the country in September to
observe Nigeria's entire transition process fielded observation
teams in three states and the federal capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Pierson promised to sponsor an extensive observation effort
during Nigeria's forthcoming state and federal elections next
year.
</P>
<P>
The Transition Monitoring Group (TMG), a coalition of 45 human
rights non-governmental organizations in Nigeria, said at a press
conference Monday that the voter turnout was reasonable and
impressive "compared to the turnout in elections in the recent
past."
</P>
<P>
The TMG which was formally accredited by the INEC to monitor
the election nationwide deployed more than 1,000 observers all
over the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the TMG, the Saturday elections were largely
peaceful and free of rancor in many voting centers across the
country despite some isolated cases of violence reported in some
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
