<HEADLINE> Pirekeev Takes Men's Free Rifle Prone Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkmenistan's Igor Pirekeev
scored 104.2 points in the final for a total of 697.2 points to
grab the men's free rifle prone title at the Asian Games here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Pirekeev, an Atlanta Olympian who registered 593 points to top
the qualification here, produced stable performance to lead all
the way to the title in the final.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Tavarit Majcharcheep won the silver medal with 693.3
points, followed by Japan's bronze medalist Naoki Kurita at 691.1.
</P>
<P>
Pirekeev, a 27-year-old from Turkmenistan's capital Ashkhabad,
said: "I did not feel pressure in the final. That was nothing
special. But the wind may cause a small problem sometimes."
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's title was his first gold in a major international
competition.
</P>
<P>
China's Li Wenjie, runner-up at the last Asian Games in
Hiroshima, finished only eighth.
</P>
<P>
In the team event, Majcharcheep, Nopparat Yavilaspradit and
Samarn Jongsuk score a total of 1,758 to give the host country
Thailand its second shooting gold following Monday's victory in
women's air rifle.
</P>
<P>
Thai shooting team manager Police Maj. Gen. Boriboon Vuthiphakdi
said the team would hand out the awards to the gold medalists but did
not disclose the detail.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyzstan carried home the silver medal with 1,752 points, only 1
point ahead of China, who won the bronze at 1,751. 
</P>
</TEXT>
