<HEADLINE> PDP Maintains Lead in Nigeria's Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The People's Democratic Party
(PDP) maintained a comfortable lead in last Saturday's Nigerian
local government elections as more results were released by the
Independent Electoral Commission (INEC).
</P>
<P>
Out of a total of 774 local council chairmanship seats
contended by the nine parties provisionally registered by the
INEC, the PDP captured 404 seats and led in 27 states as well as
the Federal Capital Territory Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The All People's Party secured 159 seats and led in two
states.
</P>
<P>
The Alliance for Democracy won 96 seats and was ahead in the
six states including Lagos, all the in the southwest.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the six parties had only one or two seats each.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's polls were the first of a series of elections on
the timetable of the transition to civil rule program as
announced by the military government of General Abdulsalam
Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
The INEC has said that only the parties which secure at least
five percent of the total votes cast in 24 or more states will
be formally registered and allowed to contend for elections
hereafter.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, INEC chairman Ephraim Akpata is expected to address
a press conference in Abuja Wednesday on the just-concluded
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
