<HEADLINE> Malaysia Dropped from U.S. Drug Producer List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
dropped Malaysia and Iran from its list of drug-producing
countries, the Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bernama quoted U.S. President Bill Clinton as saying in a
letter to Congress Monday "This year I have removed Iran and
Malaysia from the list of major drug producing countries and
designated them as countries of concern.
</P>
<P>
"Although Malaysia's geographic location makes it a feasible
transit route for heroin to the United States, as had been the
case in the past, we have no indication that drugs significantly
affecting the United States have transited the country in the past
few years," Clinton was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Bernama said the gesture may temporarily loosen bilateral
tensions between the two countries following U.S. Vice-President
Al Gore's "provocative" remarks on the "reform movement" launched
by former Malaysian deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim and U.S.
financier George Soros' call for the ouster of Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
