<P>
PARIS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The French government will spend one billion francs (170
million U.S. dollars) to finance the Commissions of Emergency Social
Aid to help the unemployed and the poor. The government is faced
with a new wave of protests by the unemployed during the
Christmas-new year season.
</P>
<P>
-- Accidents of violence are on the rise in Algeria two weeks
from the Muslim fasting month of Ramadan. About 70 people have been
killed since the beginning of December in attacks attributed to
``Islamic terrorists.'' Five people were injured in a bomb explosion
Monday in a commercial district of Algiers, while a car bomb attack
was staged against a residential district in the capital last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Russian President Boris Yeltsin has fired his chief of
administration, Valentin Yumachev, who was dubbed ``Rasputine on the
payroll.'' Yumachev would be replaced by the secretary of the
Russian Security Council, Nicolai Bordiouja, who was a former
general of the KGB.
</P>
<P>
-- The number of foreign students studying in French colleges has
dropped from 12.5 percent of the whole students' corps of France 10
years ago to the present 8.5 percent. Formalities, bureaucracy and
immigration policy are blamed for the falling enthusiasm of foreign
students to study in France. 
</P>
