<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyans Salaries to Rise Above Inflation in 1999: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan private sector workers
can expect a 1999 salary rise above the inflation rate, shows a
survey conducted by a management and audit consultants company.
</P>
<P>
The Price Waterhouse Coopers firm predicted in a survey last
week that 1999 salary increases will average 12.6 percent for
management and 13.9 percent for staff, according to an East African
Standard report on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
That will be above the anticipated average annual inflation
rate of 10 percent in calendar 1998, said the survey.
</P>
<P>
But the salary increases will be lower than that in 1998 which
registered an average 12.8 percent increase for management and
14.7 percent for staff.
</P>
<P>
Price Waterhouse Coopers surveyed 117 companies in 10 sectors
for their report, which human resource analysts said would be the
benchmark for salary increases in Kenya in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The report put the highest paid executive in Kenya at a salary
of 1.31 million Shillings (nearly 220,000 U.S. Dollars) per month
while the lowest average salary for managers in the private
sector is 10,327 Shillings (some 172 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
And the lowest paid position among the private companies
surveyed is 4,292 Shillings (about 72 Dollars) per month.
</P>
<P>
Public sector salaries are still very poor in the country,
ranging from the legislated low minimum wage of 2,852 Shillings
(48 Dollars) to 61,000 Shillings (1,017 Dollars) per month.
</P>
<P>
However, allowances are normally several times the net salary
in the public sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
