<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Infants to Be Vaccinated Against Diarrhea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 7 (Xinhua) -- All U.S. infants will be
vaccinated against the leading cause of diarrhea, the country's
top doctors said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"In order to protect against the large number of children who
need to be hospitalized, we need to give the vaccine to
everybody," said Dr. Neal Halsey of the American Academy of
Pediatrics and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
Each year, diarrhea causes three million American children
sick, with 55,000 of them hospitalized and 40 killed. The total
costs amount to some 400 million U.S. dollars nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. experts also said that in developing countries
with poor health care, diarrhea kills about one million children a
year. The vaccine promises to reduce by up to 80 percent the worst
cases of diarrhea caused by rotavirus, they added.
</P>
<P>
Three doses of the vaccine are recommended at ages of two
months, four months and six months after every U.S. baby is born.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
