<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Cambodia's acting head of state Prince Norodom
Ranariddh Tuesday gave a warm welcome to the United Nations'
decision to resume Cambodia's seat.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that now that Cambodia has a legal new
coalition government and a National Assembly which were formed in
accordance with the constitution and the results of the election,
it was very normal to resume Cambodia's U.N. seat. "Cambodia needs
the U.N. seat because it will help a lot to our country' economic
construction and social development. We hope the U.N. and the
international community will resume their aid to Cambodia," said
the prince, who is also President of the National Assembly.
(Cambodia-UN Seat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Two astronauts stepped out of the U.S. space
shuttle Endeavour on Monday for their first space walk.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the walk was to connect wires between a U.S. and
a Russian module, said the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration (NASA). With 135 tools at their disposal and
working at 240 miles above the Earth, Jerry Ross, NASA's four-time
space-walker, and James Newman, a 42-year-old physicist, clamped
the electrical connectors for power and data flow between the
Russian module Zarya and the U.S. module Unity -- the first two
components of the international space station. (US-Space Walking)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Yugoslav Prime Minister Momir Bulatovich on Monday
accused the United States of blocking Yugoslavia's return to the
international community, said the Yugoslav Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
Bulatovich was quoted as saying in an interview with a local
paper Courier that it was some big powers, first of all the United
States, that have exerted pressure on Yugoslavia in an attempt to
seek their strategic interests in this region. According to the
newspaper Vecernje Novosti, U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Saturday announced a six-month extension of the U.S. sanctions on
Yugoslavia on grounds of Belgrade's failure to meet international
demands. (Yugoslavia-US-Sanction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- French troops set up an air link on Monday to
transport more NATO soldiers into Macedonia, the Albanian news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The first 120 French members of a NATO rapid reaction force
arrived in Skopje's Petrovec Airport on four planes from southern
France's Istres air base. They will be deployed at Kumanove base,
north Skopje. British, Italian and Dutch troops, as well as more
French soldiers, are set to arrive in Macedonia within 10 days by
way of the French air link. NATO and Macedonia reached an
agreement on November 13 to station a 1,700 rapid reaction force
in the country. (Macedonia-NATO) 
</P>
</TEXT>
