<HEADLINE> Reform Improves Scientists Social Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The past two decades of reform
and opening have sparked the creativity and enthusiasm of Chinese
scientists.
</P>
<P>
Efforts over the past 20 years have proceeded under the
guidance of directions issued by late Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping, according to Zhou Guangzhao, vice-chairman of the
National People's Congress Standing Committee and president of the
China Association for Science and Technology (CAST). "Science and
technology represent the first productive force", said Zhou,
adding that the Chinese government has implemented a series of
policies which have enabled scientists to introduce a
variety of new scientific concepts.
</P>
<P>
Zhou made the comments today at a CAST meeting held to mark the
20th anniversary of the Third Plenary Session of the 11th Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) which initiated
China's reform and opening efforts. Zhou said working and living
conditions for scientists have improved greatly and the nation has
formed a favorable research environment.
</P>
<P>
Li Xueyong, vice-minister of science and technology, said that
historical changes in China over the past 20 years have been based
on the emancipation of minds.
</P>
<P>
Physicist He Zuoxiu, a well-known member of the Chinese Academy
of Sciences, said the Chinese government has adopted extensive
measures over the past two decades to improve the social status of
scientists. A recent survey revealed that Chinese citizen rank
scientists first on the list of highly respected
professionals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
