<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian City Declared Emergency as Heating System Fails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Schools and day-care centers in
Vladivostok have been closed as the Far Eastern Russian municipal
government declares a state of emergency due to its inability to
provide residents with central heating.
</P>
<P>
As the city's stock of fuel oil dwindles, half the city is
currently without heat.
</P>
<P>
Over 500 apartment buildings are currently unheated due to
major leaks from steam pipes belonging to the local power
company, Dalenergo, Interfax reported in a dispatch from
Vladivostok.
</P>
<P>
According to weather forecasts, Vladvostok's temperature on
Tuesday was at -13 to -10 degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities have appealed for help from the federal
government and told President Boris Yeltsin that the city was on
the verge of total paralysis.
</P>
<P>
Russian cities usually rely on an elaborate network of steam
pipes to deliver heat from central plants. Few apartments are
equipped with alternative heaters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
