<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Sino-Foreign Cooperative Research Groups in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) --Vast personnel resources and the
potentially huge domestic market are the main factors persuading
increasing numbers of key global businesses and institutions to
set up Sino-foreign research cooperatives in China.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Science and Technology told
Xinhua today that there are already at least over 70 Sino-foreign
cooperative research groups currently operating throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
They have come from the United States, Britain, France, Japan,
Germany and Canada, amongst other countries, to establish such
professional partnerships in big Chinese cities such as Beijing,
Shanghai, Tianjin and Guangdong, which contain large numbers of
Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the focus is on high-tech sectors
such as information, biology and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Shanghai Institute of Metallurgy, which is
attached to the Chinese Academy of Sciences, has established a
joint research center with the German company Benze to develop
packaging material for electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the Institute say the research is important to help
extend the service life of the products which in the long term
improves customer confidence.
</P>
<P>
Now, computer giants Intel and Microsoft have also established
research institutions in China for the development of their
products.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shaoqi, director of the International Cooperation
Department of the State Science and Technology Ministry, said that
the focus of Sino-foreign cooperation had been transformed from
the simple exchange visits of twenty years ago.
 Today, he pointed out, there is a two-way process of importing
and exporting each other's technology, which has been boosted by
the ongoing establishment of Sino-foreign research organizations.
</P>
<P>
Wang said he believed that this multi-layered international
cooperation has benefited China's social and economic development,
as well as encouraging research into a wide range of cutting edge
sciences.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures China now established scientific
and technological cooperation agreements with more than 150
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
In the past 20 years China has invited a total of more than
700,000 foreign experts to help it realize modernization and adapt
for the new millennium, and sent more than 300,000 of its own
scientists and technicians for training abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
