<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Mayor to Refund U.S. Bank: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Convicted Ugandan Mayor Nasser
Sebaggala will be forced to refund the 44,000 U.S. Dollars he
fraudulently withdrew from Bank Boston.
</P>
<P>
The Kampala mayor is most likely to be ordered to refund the
money in addition to serving a jail term between 21-27 months,
U.S. Assistant Attorney Theodore Chuang made the remarks in
Boston, the United States, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's newspaper New Vision Tuesday quoted Chuang as saying
that in majority of cases of fraud, the courts order for
restitution in addition to fines or imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
If the court makes an order for restitution, the mayor will
not have the risk of facing civil suits, the assistant attorney
added.
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala was convicted last Friday of eight counts including
cheating Bank Boston, transporting forged checks and making false
statements to customs officers.
</P>
<P>
He has been under detention at a U.S. federal center at Rhodes
Island and will be sentenced on February 23, 1999 by District
Court Judge Reginald Lindsay.
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala was arrested on June 13, 1998 in the U.S. after
attending an international conference in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
His conviction sent shock waves to Uganda's capital city.
</P>
<P>
Some people said that Sebaggala's fate has been engineered by
the Ugandan government because he is not a member of the ruling
National Resistance Movement while others argued that he is at
fault.
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala is the first directly-elected mayor of Kampala. He
edged to victory in April elections with controversial academic
qualifications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
