<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Warn of Resurging Sexually Transmitted Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts have warned
that a resurgence in sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) will
exacerbate the AIDS problem in China and urged related departments
and the general public to adopt preventive measures.
</P>
<P>
STDs, including gonorrhea and syphilis, virtually disappeared
over the past four decades, but are once again on the rise,
according to Professor Ye Shunzhang from the National STD Control
Center (NSCC).
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health recently confirmed that the number of
STD patients is most likely between two and four million people,
with that of carriers of HIV (human immunodeficiency virus)
suffering from the acquired immune deficiency syndrome (AIDS) also
on the rise.
</P>
<P>
"Experts predict an increase in HIV infections in the future,
with a likely drop in infections resulting from intravenous
injection of drug due to the strengthened anti-drug campaign,"
according to Ye.
</P>
<P>
Some 66 percent of an estimated 300,000 HIV carriers in China
were infected as a result of sharing contaminated needles.
</P>
<P>
Experts stress that China should not follow the same path
travelled by some African countries where unprotected sex sparked
virtual HIV epidemics. They also point out that rampant
prostitution provides a ready source for sparking STD and AIDS
epidemics.
</P>
<P>
The actual number prostitutes and customers brothel frequenters
is much bigger than the known figure, according to Zhang Konglai,
chairman of nongovernmental AIDS monitoring network.
</P>
<P>
A recent Beijing AIDS education exhibition confirmed that 20
percent of prostitutes are STD patients, with one in every 100
infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
China has adopted a cross-century program designed to control
both STDs and AIDS. The goal of the program is to maintain the
annual increasing rate for STDs under 15 percent by the year 2002,
compared to some 16 percent at present.
</P>
<P>
The State Council program encourages the use and promotion of
condoms, sex education for college and high school students, and
additional training for medical professionals treating STD cases.
</P>
<P>
The program calls for more than 85 percent of medical
institutions above the county-level to offer standard services for
diagnosing and treating STDs by the year 2002.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
