<HEADLINE> Guo Eyes Olympics after Springgold Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- China's ace diver Guo Jingjing
set her sights on the 2000 Sydney Olympics after she easily won
the women's three-meter springbaord of the Asian Games here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Guo, who got the highest score of 66.120 points
with her concluding reverse 1-1/2 somersaults with 2-1/2 twists,
amassed 547.470 points to win the gold. Her teammate Yang Lan
got the silver with 510.840.
</P>
<P>
Much-touted Irina Vyguzova of Kazakhstan only managed the
bronze with 489.990.
</P>
<P>
"My next major goal is to win in the 2000 Sydney Olympics," Guo
said. "I know it won't be easy, for the rivals there will be much
tougher than here."
</P>
<P>
"As I know, as long as I make no big mistakes, the gold should
be mine, so I feel no pressure throughout the competition, " Guo
said.
</P>
<P>
"After the games, I will work harder in preparation for the
2000 Olympics," she added.
</P>
<P>
Guo, who risked no dive with difficulty degree higher than 3.0,
said, she would try to master forward 3-1/2 somersaults after the
games.
</P>
<P>
"I have tried it, but my dive is not consistent," she said.
</P>
<P>
The only diver who had ever threatened Guo was her teammate.
The 19-year-old Yang took the lead from Guo after the first dive
with inward 2-1/2 somersaults, which was awarded 61.200 points.
</P>
<P>
But Guo won it back with her second dive, which earned her 63.9
points, and she never relinquished it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
