<HEADLINE> Finnish Kids Raise US$300,000 for Zambian AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Fifty thousand pupils in
Finland have raised about 300,000 U.S. Dollars in one day for
Zambian children orphaned by AIDS, Zambia Daily Mail reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The money was raised through Taksvarkki, a Finnish
non-governmental organization (NGO) established in 1967.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Oliver Kanene, information officer of KEPA
Zambia, a Finnish NGO partnership program, as saying that the
money would be given to Zambian AIDS orphans for various support
activities such as building orphanages and providing clothing,
food and primary education.
</P>
<P>
The fund-raising by students in Finland will continue until
March 1999, during which more money is expected to be generated
for Zambian orphans.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Zambia will have 600,000 children
orphaned by AIDS by the year 2000. However, The traditional
extended family system in the country is breaking down and
orphans usually have no one to look after them.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish NGO Taksvarkki annually picks a country and theme
in the Third World to support. The pupils and students work at
any nearest company for one day while on the same day adults can
donate a day's salary to the cause.
</P>
<P>
Zambia was picked this year and the problem was identified as
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Next year, child soldiers in Sudan will be the beneficiaries
of the annual benevolent event, according to the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
