<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Companies Pledge Not to Sell Ancient Forest Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Over 20 major
U.S. companies pledged Monday to phase out using and selling
products from trees harvested in the world's ancient forests,
according to reports from the companies concerned.
</P>
<P>
The companies involved in the project, to be formally announced
Tuesday, include Nike Inc., Dell Computer Corp., IBM Corp.,
Lockheed Martin Corp. and other 21 corporations, which agreed to
conduct an internal audit and stop purchasing wood and other
materials from companies who use products made from old-growth
lumber.
</P>
<P>
Environmental organizations say only 20 percent of the world's
old-growth forests are left and only five percent are in the
United States. Old-growth forests consist of trees hundreds of
years old that shelter many animal, bird and insect species.
</P>
<P>
In October, U.S. environmentalists began a nationwide campaign
to pressure Atlanta-based Home Depot Inc., the country's largest
retailer of home improvement supplies, to stop offering products
made of ancient redwoods and other old-growth lumber, such as
Amazon mahogany and lauan plywood from Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
They demonstrated outside 70 of the 713 Home Depot stores on
October 14, which shocked the companies concerned.
</P>
<P>
Sources say the campaign to save the ancient forest has been
intensified during the past two years and the promise by the 25
U.S. companies is a major success for the environmentalists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0248 </DOCNO>
