<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 8 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has emerged
as a key player in efforts to resolve the civil war on the Comoro
island of Anjouan which is said to have claimed 40 lives.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Ministry spokesman Marco Boni said
Monday that South Africa was one of the countries playing a
mediating role in solving the Comorian Crisis in accordance with
an Organization of African Unity (OAU) resolution.
</P>
<P>
But there was no indication that South African soldiers would
form part of a possible OAU peacekeeping force, the Star
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The fighting in the Comoros started Saturday after an
assassination attempt on self-styled Anjouan President Abdallah
Ibraham by supporters of "prime minister" Abdou Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
They are trying to prevent Ibraham from re-joining the federal
Comoro state. It is said that since leading Anjouan into
independence in 1997, Ibraham has grown disillusioned.
</P>
<P>
His rivals, however, are still fiercely determined that
Anjouan remain independent and so have violently opposed his move
to open negotiations with the federal government in capital
Moroni. 
