<HEADLINE> Kenya-EU Trade up 1.28 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Trade volume between Kenya and
the European Union (EU) has topped 77 billion Shillings (around
1.28 billion U.S. Dollars) so far this year, a senior government
official said.
</P>
<P>
The EU is a major trading partner with Kenya and most of
Kenyan goods are destined in the European market, the planning
and national development minister, George Saitoti, told local
press here Monday.
</P>
<P>
As the current chairman in office of the African Caribbean
Pacific (ACP) Council of Ministers, Saitoti just provided a
meeting in Brussels. He also attended another meeting in
Stockholm focusing on the dialogue for democratic development for
renewing the ACP-EU partnership in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
European investors have great interest in the East African
region with particular interest in the Kenyan economy, the
minister was quoted as saying by Kenya Times Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that what to be done is to package the investment
opportunities in Kenya so as to attract investors using ACP-EU
co-operation as a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
With regard to trade, Saitoti said that ACP countries are
committed to provisions of World Trade Organization (WTO) as a
regulator of international trade.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the position of ACP in future with regard to
WTO's threat to ACP states is to preserve preferential access of
ACP goods into EU market while re-orienting ACP economies to
global competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
