<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Economic Statistics Show Blurred Picture: Press </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Official statistics on Vietnam's
socio-economic development will show a blurred picture, the
Vietnam Investment Review (VIR) said in its latest issue.
</P>
<P>
The English-language weekly said "the decline in foreign
investment, disappointing budget collection and the growing trade
deficit among other problems have severely affected ambitious
development targets set by the government."
</P>
<P>
The VIR quoted a government report circulated among senior
government members as saying that in the first 11 months of 1998,
the number of foreign direct investment projects decreased 29
percent, while registered capital contributed by foreign
investment fell 49 percent in comparison to the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
The report, only released at government levels, blamed the
Asian financial crisis as the principal reason for the decline,
said the weekly.
</P>
<P>
The government report claimed that as figures stood at the end
of November, Vietnam has signed official development aid deals
totaling 1.26 billion U.S. dollars, of which 1.13 billion dollars
have been received in loans.
</P>
<P>
Trade deficit for the whole of this year is expected to rise to
2 billion dollars, accounting for approximately 22 percent of the
total value of exports and three percent higher than the target
approved by the National Assembly earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the government report, as of mid-November total
budget collection stood at 4.1 billion dollars, meeting 82.6
percent of the year's target, of which 3.2 billion dollars or 79.1
percent came from the state sector.
</P>
<P>
Total budget spending in the past 11 months stood at 4.67
billion dollars, meeting 80.2 percent of the set target.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the budget deficit stood at 568 million dollars,
meeting 66.3 percent of the target approved by the National
Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
