<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hui People in Guangxi Enjoy Normal Religious Life (1) (Guangxi Ethnic Group Series) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Editor's Note: The following is
the ninth of a series of stories featuring the fast-changing life
and culture of the Zhuang, Hui, Miao, Yao and other seven main
ethnic groups in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region,
which will mark its 40th founding anniversary on December 11.
</P>
<P>
Over many years, Bai Yumei, an elderly Hui woman of Jiucun
Village of Lingui County, Guilin City, often felt sad that she was
unable to read aloud the Koran during daily prayers because she
did not understand Arabic.
</P>
<P>
However, that situation ended three years ago when the Guilin
City Islam Association invited Ma Zhengsheng, an ahung from Gansu
Province, to the mosque of the Jiucun Village to perform those
duties.
</P>
<P>
China has a Hui population of 8.6 million, with the majority
living in the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region in the northwest and
the rest scattered around the country. Maintaining the religious
tradition of these far-flung Chinese Muslims is considered no easy
task.
</P>
<P>
"The religious atmosphere here is quite different from that of
Ningxia and Gansu," pointed out Ahung Ma.
</P>
<P>
Ahung Ma said he was quite surprised upon arrival to find that
only a few villagers, mostly the elderly, prayed.
</P>
<P>
He also discovered that only a few of the male villagers had
retained the Hui habit of wearing the traditional white cap, and that
almost all the women had given up wearing the equivalent white
scarf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts to Reclaim Land from Polders Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese water conservancy
experts believe that reclaiming land from the sea will be
one of the effective ways for China to increase land resources to
cope with its growing population.
</P>
<P>
However, Huang Linquan, deputy secretary of the China Water
Conservancy Institute, said that such land reclamation projects
must be carried out whilst also improving the environment of
rivers and marine locations.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 water conservancy officials and experts met in
Xiaoshan City of east China's Zhejiang Province to discuss various
methods for reclaiming land from the sea and also considered the
ongoing protection of the marine ecological environment.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics China has reclaimed 1.06.6
million hectares of land from the sea in the past 50 years,
reckoned to equal almost the total arable land area of Zhejiang
Province.
</P>
<P>
With a per capita arable land space of less than 0.33 hectare,
Zhejiang Province has itself reclaimed 160,000 hectares from
coastal areas in the past half a century.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that China can convert half of the existing 2
million hectares of available coastal regions for use as potential
proper land mass. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hui People (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"It is sad that we are losing so many religious customs. Now we
are helping re-establish normal religious activity in the area,"
Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Villagers, however, commented that in the past they were poor
yet still had to spend a lot of money to invite an ahung from
Guilin to preside over religious, festive or marital ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
Now, thanks to fast-improving living standards in recent years
the Hui people have been able to build mosques in their own
villages.
</P>
<P>
And as a result of Ahung Ma's presence, the mosque is becoming
as busy again as the other 35,000 plus mosques in China. Many
young villagers are also taking a more active role in their
religion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many villagers have installed bathing facilities so
that they can take a shower before praying, as required by
custom.
</P>
<P>
"In the past we had to worry about how to make a living and so
neglected our religion," said Bai Xianfa, a member of the Jiucun
Village Islam Association. "Now people have become wealthier they
have more time to attend the mosque," he added
</P>
<P>
Officials in the autonomous region stress that though there are
only just over 19,000 Hui people living in Guangxi, their religion
and customs are fully respected.
</P>
<P>
Yi Tixiang, an enterprise manager, said that his religious
beliefs have never detrimentally affected his career. On the
contrary, he said, his leaders have always demonstrated their
support for the Hui staff and wish them well on Muslim festivals.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
