<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Injuried Chinese Gymnast Keeps hope for Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Lu Yufu, one of China's top
gymnasts who injured his knee last Wedenday in pre-Asian Games
prectices here, is still keeping alive his hope to compete in the
2000 Sydney Olympic Games, Chinese gymnastics team head coach
Huang Yubin said to Xinhua here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Lu Yufu was sent home on Sunday and received a thorough
exemination on Monday at the No. 3 Hospital of Beijing Medical
College (BMC), the best hospital for sports injuries in China.
</P>
<P>
"They called from Beijing Monday night and said Lu's injury was
not as serious as we thought before," said Huang, "the professors
said his front and collateral ligaments were only partly
disrupted, not severed as we worried.
</P>
<P>
"The professors will give an operation on the knee, and Lu may
need two or three months to recover before he could compete
again." added Huang.
</P>
<P>
Lu was not the first Chinese top gymnast to suffer such an
injury. "China's former world and Olympic champion Huang Liping
also tore his knee ligament but he made a successful comeback with
the help of doctors and professors at No 3. Hospital of BMC."
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Lu, a key member of the team which won the 1997
world championships, tore his knee ligament in practice on
vaulting horse, his specialty in which he holds the world unique
movement named "Lu Yufu Jump".
</P>
<P>
"Lu is the leading gymnast in vaulting horse and floor
exercises. He is also very strong in all-around event," Huang
said, "I hope he could come back before next September's world
championship if the treatment goes well."
</P>
<P>
Lu's backup Zhao Sheng performed well on the pommel horse and
the rings to anchor China's victory in Monday's team competition,
the seventh in a row for China since the 1974 Asian Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
