<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan MPs Want Museveni's Brother Tried </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Some Members of Parliament
(MPs) of Uganda demanded that Salim Saleh, President Yoweri
Museveni's younger brother, be tried for over the Uganda
Commercial Bank (UCB) saga.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Press Secretary Hope Kivengere told Xinhua in a
telephone interview Tuesday morning that she did not know whether
the president had responded to the MPs' demand.
</P>
<P>
Saleh should not be left to go scot-free and instead he should
be imprisoned for possible perjury, Tuesday's New Vision daily
quoted some MPs as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
They argued that Saleh admitted buying the 49 percent shares
in the UCB through Greeenland Investment, a fact he even denied
before Parliament in November. Lying under oath is a criminal
offense.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Saleh, also a senior presidential advisor on
security and defense, admitted secretly buying the shares of a
Malaysian company in the UCB through Greenland Investment where
he is a shareholder. The next day he tendered resignation and
was accepted by the president.
</P>
<P>
Museveni described his brother's resignation as a curtain
raiser in the country's campaign against corruption among
government officials.
</P>
<P>
Some MPs predicted that the worst for the government is yet to
come. They said Saleh had always been referred to as
indispensable and this had partly contributed to his misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
The Westmont, another Malaysian company, bought the 49 percent
shares of the UCB in 1997. According to the agreement between
the Ugandan government and the company, the buyer is not allowed
to transfer the purchased shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
