<HEADLINE> Australian Thorpe Posted as 1998 Male Star Swimmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen-year-old Ian Thorpe
of Sydney was officially named U.S. Swimming World magazine's
1998 men's international swimmer on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The teenager overwhelmed some great figures in world swimming,
such as Russian Alex Popov and Australian Kieren Perkins.
</P>
<P>
Thorpe became Australia's youngest men's world swimming
champion in Perth by winning the 400m freestyle earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
At the Kuala Lumpur Commonwealth Games, he won four golds and
also was a member of Australia's world record beating 4x200m
freestyle relay team.
</P>
<P>
Thorpe broke 400m freestyle world record, held by New
Zealand's Olympic champion Danyon Loader, at the Australian
short-course titles just after the Commonwealth Games, clocking 3
minutes 39.82 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The uprising swimmer will meet new challenge at the World Cup
meets in Sydney and Hobart in next January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
