<HEADLINE> Kenyan Parliament to Debate Environment Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan parliament is
expected to debate after the Christmas holidays the bill on
environmental law that has already been approved by the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Solicitor-General Aaron Ringera said at the Indian Ocean port
city of Mombasa Monday that the government had reached a
milestone in finalizing a draft framework on environmental law.
</P>
<P>
"Parliament is going on recess so it is not possible to
present the motion before the present session," Ringera said.
"However, efforts are being made to table it at the first
available opportunity."
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's East African Standard newspaper quoted Ringera as saying
that the bill was a framework of legislation that set out various
institutions used to enforce environmental standards and
addresses all aspects of environment.
</P>
<P>
"We had separate legislation dealing with water, forestry and
factories but with this new bill, we are going to have a more
comprehensive legislation developed with a lot of expertise," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He added a common kind of legislation is likely to be enacted
in all the three east African countries -- Kenya, Uganda and
Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
