<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sending Less Greeting Cards to Protect Trees, Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Attractive cards offering
seasons greeting at Christmas, New Year's and other special
occasions are on the one hand very nice, but on the other hand
consume an exorbitant number of trees.
</P>
<P>
One tree is needed to produce 4,000 greeting cards, according
to a survey conducted by China Environmental Protection Fund
(CEPF).
</P>
<P>
The survey revealed that Beijingers alone sent over 30 million
greetings cards during 1997, with the volume consuming over 10,000
trees which had grown for at least 10 years.
</P>
<P>
"Fewer cards equates to more trees", according to the CEPF, the
Communist Youth League of China and both the All-China Federation
of Trade Unions and All-China Women's Federation.
</P>
<P>
Students from the Bajiao Middle School and 10 other elementary
and middle schools in Beijing recently urged Mayor Jia Qinglin to
promote the campaign of "fewer cards to protect trees".
</P>
<P>
Today's edition of Beijing Daily frontpaged a letter from the
Mayor expressing his appreciation and support for the students.
</P>
<P>
"We will be able to save large forest areas if everyone will
send one less card," according to the mayor, who urged people from
all walks of life to answer the children's call and act to protect
the environment.
</P>
<P>
The CEPF urges people to mail fewer greeting cards in future to
help save forests.
</P>
<P>
The organization noted that telephone calls and E-mail provide
good alternatives.
</P>
<P>
Dragonair, a regional airline headquartered in Hong Kong, has
announced it will not send greeting cards to clients and
business partners during the forthcoming holiday season as part of
an effort to help preserve the environment.
</P>
<P>
Chinese environmentalists point out 250,000 trees are required
to produce the one billion cards mailed worldwide on an annual
basis.
</P>
<P>
The production of paper for greeting cards also threatens the
environment when paper mills, especially smaller ventures lacking
adequate waste processing facilities, discharge untreated
wastewater into rivers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
