<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Support for New Zealand Labor Party Rising: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The gap between the National
Party,
the ruling party in New Zealand, and the Labor Party, the major
opposition party in the country, has widened in the latest New
Zealand
Herald-DigiPoll survey, which shows the latter could govern if an
election were held now.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Press Association (NZPA) reported Tuesday that
the
poll put support for the Labor Party at 51 percent among committed
voters,
up five points on the previous poll in August. Support for the
National
Party is down one point to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
The minor parties are the biggest losers in the swing to the
Labor
Party, with support for the Alliance dropping four points to six
percent
and support for ACT NZ dropping below the five percent threshold
for
gaining seats under the current voting system.
</P>
<P>
NZ First has regained a small amount of support, rising two
points to
3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The poll has a margin of error of 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The latest polls show that the support rates for the Labor
Party
always have been close to 50 percent. According to the results of
these
polls, the Labor Party with its own votes plus the votes it gets
from
minor parties that fail to obtain at least five percent of the
nationwide
party votes would be able to organize a single party government.
But the
Labor Party has up to now kept its promise of forming a coalition
with
the Alliance if it wins in election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
