<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand to Reform Roading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Transport
Minister Maurice Williamson gave a press conference here Tuesday,
announcing Government's wide-ranging proposals to reform roading.
</P>
<P>
"Our road system is struggling to keep up with changing
demands. This is evident in urban congestion and our difficulties
in funding major new developments. In many areas roads are
carrying traffic loads they weren't designed for, pushing up
maintenance costs and making them less safe," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the proposals, which are issued in a consultation
document, the roading activities of the country's 74 territorial
local authorities would be amalgamated into between four and eight
local road companies to run local roads. Transit New Zealand would
continue to operate State highways but would become a
government-owned company. Transfund New Zealand would continue its
role of providing road funding and would also become a
government-owned company.
</P>
<P>
The document also includes proposals to enforce the Road Use
Levy to clearly distinguish it from the general taxation on fuels
and to permit public road companies to introduce tolls on specific
roads and facilities and introduce congestion prices to restrain
traffic demand on heavily used routes.
</P>
<P>
The proposals will ensure roads will not be privatized, the
present network will be retained, communities will continue to
have a say in road management and everyone will have the same
access they have today, Minister Williamson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Resume Fish Exports to EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Kenya will resume fish exports
to the European Union (EU) at the beginning of the next year, said
Kenyan Planning and National Development Minister George Saitoti.
</P>
<P>
On his return Sunday from a crucial meeting between the African,
Caribbean and Pacific countries (ACP) and the EU, Saitoti said
that the country's fish exports had featured during the
meetings.
</P>
<P>
"Kenyan fish will be allowed in the EU market by the end of
the month," Tuesday's East African Standard quoted the minister
as saying.
</P>
<P>
A technical evaluation team from the EU recently visited fish
producing regions of the east African countries, namely Kenya,
Uganda and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The EU countries banned Kenyan fish exports in January this
year over the outbreak of cholera at the height of the El Nino
induced rains.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's fish exports is estimated at four billion Shillings
(67.2 million U.S. Dollars) every year with major markets being
in Holland, Britain, Spain, Japan, Israel and Australia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
