<HEADLINE> UNICEF Launches World's Children Report in S. Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) Tuesday launched the 1999 State of the World's
Children Report at a ceremony here, which coincides with the
celebration of World Human Rights Day.
</P>
<P>
Colin Glennie, UNICEF Representative in Sri Lanka, told the
ceremony that education is a basic human right, while nearly a
billion people or a sixth of the world's population are illiterate
and most of them are women.
</P>
<P>
The report, issued annually by the Executive Director of
UNICEF, focuses this time on education for all with emphasis on
education of girls and quality of education. It aims to raise the
level of awareness and stimulate discussion on the state of
children.
</P>
<P>
Glennie said that education for all is "one of the best
investment" governments can make in achieving sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
He said Sri Lanka has made remarkable progress over the past
decades, but much remains to be done about the quality of
education and education reform.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Deputy Minister of Education and Higher Education
Viswa Warnapala also spoke at the ceremony, pledging that Sri
Lanka would ensure universal primary education by 2001, which is a
basic strategy of the government on education reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
