<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Wants Expanded Trade With India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is expected to stress
the need for expanding bilateral trade with India at a
Bangladesh-India trade review that starts here Tuesday, to narrow
a widening trade gap in India's favor.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh was likely to take up some issues to remove
hindrances to exports to its mighty neighbor at the review, which
is taking place against the backdrop of Dhaka's growing concern
over the huge trade gap, The Independent daily newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The trade review would end Wednesday with the signing of
documents to renew the existing Bangladesh-India trade agreement.
The renewal takes place every three years since the signing of the
agreement in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh was expected to take up the zero tariff issue for
wider access of the country's exports to the Indian market, as an
important remedy to reduce the trade gap, now at about 40 billion
taka (825 million U.S. dollars) a year, and twice as much if
informal trade figures were added.
</P>
<P>
The report said that despite repeated appeals by Dhaka, New
Delhi has yet to grant zero tariff access to substantive
Bangladesh exports, excluding a few irrelevant items.
</P>
<P>
Items such as chemical fertilizer and dry fish were previously
given zero tariff but were not imported from Bangladesh, and
spring water, which was not produced in Bangladesh, was in the
zero tariff category.
</P>
<P>
Items like tea and jute carpets, Bangladesh's two major
exports, have not yet been given reduced tariff facilities by the
Indian side, which had only reduced tariff on some items that
Bangladesh occasionally exported, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh was facilitating the access of Indian goods by
allowing unloading of trucks at its border Customs posts, but
Bangladesh exporters did not enjoy the same facility in India,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries remains heavily in favor of
India. During the last fiscal year (July 1997-June 1998) till May
this year, Bangladesh imported 921.73 million dollars' worth of
goods from India, while its exports to the latter stood at only
65.58 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh mainly exports raw hides, leather, vegetable fat and
textile goods to India, and imports textile items, vegetable
products, mineral products, base metals, vehicles and consumer
items from India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Flood Control Projects Yield Encouraging Returns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The investment of Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region in south China in flood control
projects has paid off as they helped reduce losses caused by
flooding this year.
</P>
<P>
When you invest one yuan (about 8.28 U.S. dollars) in flood
control projects, you will get at least 40 yuan in return. This
has become the common sense among the people in the city of
Guiping and Pingyuan County.
</P>
<P>
Flood control projects enabled Guiping and Pingyuan to reduce
losses resulting from this year's heavy summer flooding by more
than three billion yuan, or 40 times more than total investments
in related projects.
</P>
<P>
Various other cities in Guangxi have had similar experiences.
One is Wuzhou, a major industrial city, whose 50 million yuan
investment to reinforce levees reduced losses caused by this
year's devastating flooding by some two billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Liuzhou, the region's industrial base, was hit by the worst
flooding on record in 1996, with economic losses soaring to over
7.7 billion yuan. The city has since launched a large-scale flood
control project at a cost of over 1.1 billion yuan, part of which
comes from the central government.
</P>
<P>
A number of other Guangxi cities followed suite and effectively
reduced this year's flood losses by over 25 billion yuan, or some
66 percent less than the level in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi has invested over a billion yuan in water conservancy
projects over the past couple of years, or 8.3 percent of total
investments over the past 40-odd years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
