<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S.Lankan Parties Ready for Local Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Nominations close Tuesday
afternoon for Sri Lanka's elections to North Western Provincial
Council (NWPC), which comprises the two districts of Kurunegala
and Puttalam.
</P>
<P>
Political parties and independent candidates will be seeking
election to 35 seats in Kurunegala and 15 seats in Puttalam
district.
</P>
<P>
Following the dissolution of the provincial council in
mid-November, the Elections Commissioner has called for the
nomination of candidates from December 1 to 8 for new polls.
However, the major parties began to propose their candidates only
when time is running out.
</P>
<P>
The two main contenders for the elections are the ruling
People's Alliance (PA) and the main opposition United National
Party (UNP).
</P>
<P>
The UNP handed over its nominations for the Puttalam District
Monday together with the Sri Lanka Progressive Front (SLPF). The
PA is expected to hand over its nominations for the Puttalam
District Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Both the PA and the UNP together with the Jantha Vimukthi
Peramuna are expected to hand over their nomination lists for the
Kurunegala District Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In Parliament Monday Deputy Minister of Health S.B. Nawinna and
UNP Member of Parliament Jayawickrama Perera resigned their seats
to lead their respective parties at the elections. One of them
will be the next Chief Minister of the NWPC according to the
results of the election.
</P>
<P>
The election is expected to generate violence and the UNP has
sought police protection for their candidates when they hand over
nominations at Kurunegala Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They have made representations to the Inspector General of
Police Lucky Kodituwakku that they had information that the PA was
preparing for violence at Kurunegala Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Elections to five other Provincial Councils in the country,
which were scheduled for last August, were postponed indefinitely
on grounds of security.
</P>
<P>
The government sought to pass legislation to legalize the
postponement but the Supreme Court ruled that the draft
legislation was ultra vires the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Now the government proposes to hold the elections in the course
of next year for the five Provincial Councils.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here say the Provincial Council elections are widely
seen as mini-general elections at which the government tests its
strength and the opposition its popularity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmentalists Say Artificial Snow Harmful to Alps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Commission for
Protecting the Alps on Monday called for a curb on artificial snow
facilities in the Alpine mountains, warning that too much such
snow designed for skiing would be harmful to the environment.
</P>
<P>
According to the commission, less snowfall in recent years has
prompted skiing companies to resort to man-made snow in their bid
to attract tourists.
</P>
<P>
Helmut Moroder, head of the commission, cited serious
consequences caused by oversized man-made snow: endangering
aquatic species, shortening growing period of alpine plants and
leaving behind harmful chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The commission said the number of artificial snow facilities
stood at 549 in 1996, covering some 6,600 hectares in the Alps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0292 </DOCNO>
