<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Envoy Urges Australia to Accept Nuclear Waste Dump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States Tuesday
publicly urged its ally Australia to accept a proposal by an
American company to establish a dump for the world's nuclear
waste.
</P>
<P>
Robert Gallucci, U.S. President Bill Clinton's special envoy on
weapons of mass destruction, Tuesday told an Australian national
radio that the proposal would not only be profitable for Australia
but would also be a service to the international community.
</P>
<P>
"Australia could play a role in that, I think it would make a
tremendous contribution to international security," he told
Australian Broadcasting Corporation News Radio.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the Australian federal government has offered no
public support for the plan, and last week Environment Minister
Robert Hill denied "any ministerial" discussions about it.
</P>
<P>
The Seattle-based company Pangea has been quietly floating the
proposal for two years.
</P>
<P>
It was forced to go public with its plans last week when green
groups uncovered a promotional video extolling Australia's
qualities as a dump site.
</P>
<P>
Australia had a history of being active in promoting the
non-proliferation of nuclear weapons of mass destruction, the
envoy said.
</P>
<P>
"I can't help but think that the economics would be very
favorable for a commercial arrangement that involved addressing
the needs of so many countries who do not have the geology for the
long term storage of spent nuclear fuel or radioactive waste," he
said.
</P>
<P>
With the majority of its 18 million population living in
coastal cities, Australia has vast and uninhabited desert inland
on its continent, which covers 7.68 million sq km.
</P>
<P>
Gallucci acknowledged that the U.S. had produced much of the
world's spent nuclear fuel but said he doubted it would be
possible to site the dump there.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know enough about the geology of the United States,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"But I don't think the politics in the United States would
sustain (the idea of storing the world's nuclear waste in the
US)."
</P>
<P>
"We're having difficulty storing our own spent fuel ... I don't
know that we could succeed in storing the spent fuel from all the
countries.
</P>
<P>
"This is fundamentally a political issue ... (based on) the
resistance of people to taking in other people's spent fuel."
</P>
<P>
Gallucci said if Australians decided the proposal was not in
their public interest that would be their sovereign right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
