<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Asian Exports Continue to Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- When a financial crisis hit Asia
18 months ago, economists expressed confidence that the sharp
currency depreciation in local currencies would boost exports and
that the faster export growth would drive the region out of the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
But 18 months later, analysts found that Asia's exports were
still declining rather than increasing on the back of devalued
currencies.
</P>
<P>
Why did currency devaluations fail to spur an export recovery?
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the strong dollar should be partly blamed for the
failure.
</P>
<P>
In the past 18 months, while currencies in Southeast Asian
countries depreciated by 30 percent to 70 percent, export growth
in local currency terms has increased dramatically in these
countries. But when the local currencies have been changed into
dollars, export revenues have declined substantially in the
region.
</P>
<P>
During the first six months of 1998, exports in Thailand and
Malaysia sank 4 percent and 10 percent respectively in dollar
terms. South Korea saw only 3.6 percent growth for the first half
of the year, but negative growth in recent months. Indonesia's
exports also dropped 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The collapse in export prices has a more grave effect on the
export growth, since it is cancelling out much gains in export
volumes.
</P>
<P>
When local currencies have remained on a downturn in the past
year, Asian exporters in the crisis-hit countries have been
competing to lower their dollar prices. As dollars are worth more
in local currency terms, exporters can afford to lower prices
without hurting profits.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, export volume grew by 16 percent in the first
three months of this year, but the gains were crushed by an
equivalent fall in export prices.
</P>
<P>
According to a U.S. government report, import prices for Asian
products have dropped by 15 percent to 20 percent recently,
compared with a 5 percent drop in prices for European products.
</P>
<P>
While Asian exporters are competing to lower their prices,
over-
capacity in the region and weaker demand of electronics on the
world
market have also crushed export prices.
</P>
<P>
Chip makers were hit during the first six months of this year
by a massive drop in dynamic random access memory prices on global
markets as
semiconductors from Japan, China's Taiwan, the United States and
South Korea flooded markets.
</P>
<P>
Prices of 64 megabit DRAMS have dropped to around nine dollars
from around 14 to 15 dollars at the beginning of the year, while
prices of 16 megabit DRAMS have dropped to around 1.5 to 1.8
dollars recently from about 10 dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
As electronics products have accounted for over 50 percent of
the total export revenues in some Asian countries, the region has
been hurt badly by the lower prices on the world market.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Asia is paying a high price for relying too
heavily on electronics for export earnings.
</P>
<P>
Besides, much of the stagnation in exports comes from weak
demand in the Asian region itself, and particularly in Japan.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, about half of products were exported to countries
within the region. But after the regional crisis, most countries
have cut their imports.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese markets sucks 12 percent of Asia's exports, but
Japan's economic recession and the weak yen trimmed its imports
from Asian countries by more than 10 percent for the first half of
the year.
</P>
<P>
Higher prices for imported materials after currency
devaluations and a shortage of working capital are also squeezing
export industries in Asia.
</P>
<P>
All these problems which are affecting Asia's exports may
continue for some time, because diversification of export products
may need years to complete. A rebound in prices depends on the
supply and demand on the world market and the squeezing export
financing could be eased only
after banks reduce their non-performing loans, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
As Asia's growth engine, the region's exports could hardly
contribute
more to an economic recovery in 1999, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
