<HEADLINE> Tonnage of World Merchant Ships Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The total tonnage of the
world's merchant shipping increased in the past year, according to
a latest report by the Shipowners Association of Norway obtained
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
By July 1, 1998, the association said, the number of merchant
ships weighing more than 300 tons had reached 38,619, with a total
tonnage of 494.1 million.
</P>
<P>
The over-all deadweight tonnage of the world merchant shipping
reached 751.2 million, up by 2.4 percent from 12 months before,
the association said.
</P>
<P>
Although there were ups and downs in the deadweight tonnage of
merchant shipping in the world's top 10 shipping countries, the
same top 10 remained in their previous places in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Panama, with 4,877 ships and a total tonnage of 93.2 million,
continued to hold the lead, followed by Liberia, Greece, the
Bahamas, Malta, Cyprus, Norway, Singapore, Japan and China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
