<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clash for Judo Between Tradition and Modernization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The International Judo
Federation (IJF) president said here on Monday judo should usher
in reform as it's getting more and more popular in the world but
Aisa's chief said no.
</P>
<P>
The IJF president Park Yong Sung said that judo has become an
international sport, so it should be changed at the request of the
world.
</P>
<P>
"Judo has become a world's sport like football, basketball and
volleyball," Park said. "It does not belong only to Asia, Europe
or Africa."
</P>
<P>
But Jagdish Tytler, president of Asian Judo Federation (AJF)
said that judo has changed enough and should have no more radical
reform.
</P>
<P>
"Asia is the birthplace of judo," Tytler said. "It's time for
Asia to stand out. Asia should dominate the sport."
</P>
<P>
Judo, founded by Japan in 1882, became an Olymic medal event in
1964, and enjoyed a rapid development since.
</P>
<P>
In the Atlanta Olympic Games, Belgium and France broke the
manipulation of Japan and South Korea to take one gold medal
apiece.
</P>
<P>
Hcws Vandeweghe of the Netherlands, a veteran sportswriter of
monthly Sport International, said that there are a lot of judo
clubs in Belgium and France.
</P>
<P>
"The two gold medals from the Atlanta Olympic Games was really
a promotion for the sport," he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, western countries insisted the athletes must play in
colorful sportswear on the mat instead of the tradional white
colors to fit the need of television broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
Under such pressure, the IJF passed a proposal that judocas can
choose either white or blue in the future international
competitions.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing that the decision may boost the popularity of judo,
Tytler said that there had been enough changes to the sport.
</P>
<P>
"To enter the Olympic family, judo is not what it was," he
said. "The original rule has been changed, the color has been
changed, what they will do with judo?"
</P>
<P>
Tytler, who has been AJF president for four years, said Judo
has a deeper meaning than a face-to-face match between two
athletes.
</P>
<P>
"Judo has an spiritual meaning," he said. "It should remain a
sport which can purify people's heart."
</P>
<P>
But Park, a reformer who was voted the IJF president in 1996,
put it more simple: "Judo is judo. It's just a sport for gold
medals. I don't understand the Japanese' meaning." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0311 </DOCNO>
