<HEADLINE> China to Launch '99 Eco-Tourism Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- China plans to host a series of
ecological tourism activities in 1999, according to the China
National Tourism Administration (CNTA).
</P>
<P>
The CNTA has listed 10 major projects, including wild animal
appreciation, cycling and desert tours. The opening ceremony for
the '99 China Eco-Tourism will be held in south China's Guangdong
Province on January 1.
</P>
<P>
The CNTA welcomes tourists to visit famous Chinese scenic sites
such as Taishan and Huangshan mountains, 19 state nature reserves,
and 119 forest parks.
</P>
<P>
China will hold 31 tourism festivals during 1999, including the
Xiangshan Red Leaf Festival in Beijing and the Nanhui Peach
Blossom Festival in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The CNTA, State Environmental Protection Administration, State
Forestry Administration and the Chinese Academy of Sciences
jointly planned related activities.
</P>
<P>
China had a total of 57.59 million overseas tourists in 1997, a
12.6-percent increase from the previous year when the number of
overseas tourists exceeded 50 million for the first time.  
</P>
