<HEADLINE> Colombian President Calls for Anti-Poverty Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Colombian
President Andres Pastrana on Monday called on Latin American
governments to take further measures against widespread poverty.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the Mexican Senate, Pastrana also called for
joint anti-drug and anti-crime actions to curb growing discontent
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian president ascribed poverty in Latin America to
economic globalization. "Never before has so much wealth been
concentrated by so few people, but never before have so many
people depended on the minimum to survive," Pastrana told the
Mexican lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
"Employment is the new name of peace," Pastrana said, stressing
that widespread drug-related violence and corruption in the region
could be controlled if the governments acted "with intelligence
and humanity".
</P>
<P>
Pastrana, who arrived in Mexico on Sunday night for a two-day
official visit, will sign six cooperation accords on fight against
drug, trade, education, tourism and culture.
</P>
<P>
He is accompanied by several cabinet members and a 100-strong
business delegation. 
