<HEADLINE> Mexico to Remain Outside OPEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Mexico will not join the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) and remain an
independent oil producer, Mexico's Energy Secretariat announced on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement rejected rumors that Mexico would join OPEC
with Russia and Oman in an effort to lift oil prices from a nearly
12-year low.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said Mexico and the two other countries would lose
more than they could gain by joining OPEC, which would commit them
to a policy of cutting crude output. Mexico has expressed
unwillingness to make further output cuts.
</P>
<P>
The Energy Secretariat affirmed that Mexico would continue to
cooperate with OPEC and non-OPEC oil producers to boost world
crude prices.
</P>
<P>
Mexico, together with OPEC members Saudi Arabia and Venezuela,
were instrumental in convincing other countries to cut their
production this year, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's state-owned oil company, Petroleos Mexicanos (Pemex),
exported 1.65 million barrels a day in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
