<HEADLINE> Reno: No Independent Investigation on Clinton-Gore Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno on Monday declined to order an independent counsel to
investigate President Bill Clinton and Vice President Al Gore over
political advertisements financed by the Democratic Party during
the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
Following a 90-day preliminary investigation, Reno concluded
that further investigation by an outside prosecutor was not
warranted.
</P>
<P>
She said her announcement marked the end of the Justice
Department's investigation into whether the so-called issue
advertisements violated the federal criminal law.
</P>
<P>
At the heart of the allegations was whether Clinton and Gore
tried to circumvent campaign spending limits through the 46
million U.S. dollars in television advertising that was paid for
by the Democratic Party, but designed to promote their re-election.
</P>
<P>
Reno's decision was particularly good news for Clinton in a
week when he faces a possible impeachment vote by the U.S. House
of Representatives Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
"I have found there are no reasonable grounds for further
criminal investigation," Reno said in a two-page statement.
</P>
<P>
"I have determined that there is clear and convincing evidence
that neither the president nor any other covered person acted with
criminal intent in connection with the issue advertisements," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, already the target of independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's investigation, could have been dogged in his last two
years in office by an outside prosecutor if Reno had decided more
investigation was needed for the campaign allegations.
</P>
<P>
The White House hailed Reno's decision. "As we have said all
along, the president and the Clinton-Gore campaign complied with
the spirit and letter of the law. We are gratified by this
decision," White House spokeswoman Amy Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Republicans in Congress, who have long demanded an
independent counsel to investigate the 1996 campaign, strongly
attacked Reno's decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
