<HEADLINE> Argentina, Brazil Fail to Agree on Free Sugar Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Talks between Brazil and
Argentina on free sugar trade within the South Common Market
(Mercosur) have turned out to be bitter as the two sides failed to
reach any agreement, a Brasilian diplomatic source said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sugar is among the few items whose trade is restricted within
the four-nation bloc, which consists of Argentina, Brazil,
Paraguay and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
Argentina has slapped a 22 percent tariff on Brazilian sugar,
which gets government subsidies to keep alive a dying alcohol-fuel
sector and to protect hundreds of thousands of cane growers from
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Foreign Ministry's director of integration affairs,
Renato Marques, said the talks would have to start again from
scrap.
</P>
<P>
The sugar disputes are threatening the unity of the Mercosur
bloc, already under shadows of grievances over milk and car trade.
</P>
<P>
South American economists said the road to free trade in the
region, which used to be smooth, has been made rough by the Asian
financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
