<HEADLINE> Corruption Costs Indonesia 238 Mln dollars Since May: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's corruption cases
recorded from May through to the second quarter of the 1998-99
fiscal year ending March 31 have cost the country a loss of 1.76
trillion rupiah (238 million U.S. dollars), the Indonesian
Observer reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Development and Finance Supervisory Body (BPKP)
Soedarjono told lawmakers in a hearing here on Monday that
corrupt, collusive and nepotistic practices had been recorded
since the Development Reform Cabinet under President B.J. Habibie
took office in May.
</P>
<P>
Soedarjono said the cases were divided into corruption (TPK) or
pure corruption cases, and non-corruption cases (non-TPK), which
are technically not corruption cases, but which resulted in
causing damage to the nation.
</P>
<P>
As of the second quarter of the current fiscal year, TPK cases
accounted for 219 billion rupiah and 205.5 million U.S. dollars
while non-TPK cases made up 27.9 billion rupiah.
</P>
<P>
"Those figures bring total losses indicated by the BPKP to
246.9 billion rupiah plus 205.5 million U.S. dollars. With an
exchange rate of 7,400 rupiah a U.S. dollar, the losses total over
1.767 trillion rupiah," he said.
</P>
<P>
Soedarjono said the BPKP has investigated 8,435 development
projects worth 21.2 trillion rupiah.
</P>
<P>
"Our findings show that of the total project value,
irregularities in 21 departments as well as non-departmental
bodies have caused a loss of 117.3 billion rupiah. The largest
contributors to the loss are the Mines and Energy, Public Works,
Culture and Education and the Transportation Departments,"
Soedarjono said.
</P>
<P>
President Habibie, who took over from Soeharto on May 21,
pledged thorough reforms in order to create a government free of
corrupt, collusive and nepotistic practices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
