<HEADLINE> Astronauts Walk to Work From U.S. Space Shuttle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Two astronauts stepped out
of the U.S. space shuttle Endeavour on Monday for their first
space walk.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the walk was to connect wires between a U.S. and
a Russian module, said the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration (NASA).
</P>
<P>
With 135 tools at their disposal and working at 240 miles above
the Earth, Jerry Ross, NASA's four-time space-walker, and James
Newman, a 42-year-old physicist, clamped the electrical connectors
for power and data flow between the Russian module Zarya and the
U.S. module Unity -- the first two components of the international
space station,
</P>
<P>
Monday's space walk, one of the three scheduled during
Endeavour's 12-day flight, will take the astronauts six hours.
When all the 40 connectors are joined, flight controllers will
turn on the power inside the fledgling station.
</P>
<P>
NASA's officials said that the U.S-built Unity, a connecting
passageway, needs the solar power generated by the Zarya control
module to survive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
