<HEADLINE> Brazil Sees Sharp Drop in Car Output, Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's automobile
output and sales in January-November this year fell by more than
22 percent from the same period last year, a national car maker
group said Monday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.5 million cars were produced in Brazil by last
month, 22.76 percent less than by November 1997, while automobile
sales dropped by 22.55 percent, with over 1.4 million cars sold.
</P>
<P>
Car demand in the country fell by 21.91 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the overall decline to rising stockpiles,
high interest rates and soaring unemployment.
</P>
<P>
But Brazil received more than four billion U.S. dollars from
its car sales abroad in the January-November period, up by 16.11
percent from the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Car plants dismissed nearly 10,000 workers in the
past year, while giving temporary leave to 13,000 others, keeping
less than 100,000 employees on the job. 
</P>
