<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Army Still Combat Effective, Says Army Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian army maintains
sufficient fighting capacity despite a shortage in military
expenditures, Commander of Army Peter Shulyak said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held by the Defense Ministry,
Shulyak said that before the year 2000, the army would focus on
training the newly-founded No.1 missile division, its containment
forces and airborne mobile troops.
</P>
<P>
He said the army headquarters would also make efforts to
increase the number of tanks and build helicopter troops as
planned.
</P>
<P>
However, Shulyak pointed out that due to a lack of financial,
material and technical guarantees, the army finished only 70
percent of its shooting training programs, 4.6 percent of its
vehicle driving programs and 40 percent of the air unit's flying
programs.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, more than 30,000 officers were ill-housed and
had not been paid for three to six months.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian army currently boasts an army staff of 180,000,
with an establishment of five corps, 11 tanks and mechanized
divisions, seven mechanized brigades, two artillery divisions, two
training divisions and 40 other brigades of various services.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian ground forces account for 56 percent of the
country's total military staff excluding the civilian members.
</P>
