<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Infant Deaths Down, Life Expectancy Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. infant mortality rates
reached their lowest level in history last year and the average
life expectancy of Americans rose to an all-time high of 76 years,
as shown by official statistics released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Teen pregnancies, as measured by the number of live births,
fell by 3 percent, continuing a downward trend that started six
years ago, according to data compiled by a research arm of the
Center for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 infant mortality rate, a measure of the number of
deaths before a baby turns one year of age, was 7.1 deaths per
1,000 births. That was about 3 percent lower than the 1996 rate
of 7.3 deaths per 1,000 live births.
</P>
<P>
The drop in infant mortality was recorded despite a 7.5 percent
increase in the number of low birth-weight babies, and an increase
of about 2 percent in the number of births by women in late
childbearing years. Pregnancy and birth complications are more
common among older women.
</P>
<P>
Medical science is combating such potential complications by
developing improved ways to treat and care for underweight and
premature babies, said Bernard Guyer of the Johns Hopkins School
of Hygiene and Public Health, who analyzed the government data.
</P>
<P>
Yet despite the improvement in infant death rates, "We still
rank pretty poorly" compared with other industrial countries,
Guyer added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
