<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Power and Heating System Saves Energy in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- A new power and heating
installation is expected to improve the utilization rate of energy
and save one third on the cost of electricity in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The new system code-named "Energy-Loving Island" is designed to
replace the traditional boiler in buildings and to serve both as
heater and power generator. The energy, fueled by light diesel oil
or natural gas, can be transferred to large power grids to provide
a constant power supply and avoid possible power outages caused by
routine power grid checks or accidents.
</P>
<P>
The system will be used at the Pudong International Airport and
the Japanese-funded Global Financial Center in Pudong. The method
is already being used in the western world. Statistics show that
10 percent of the total power in Europe, even 30 percent in some
countries, is generated this way.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has 3,000 high buildings or skyscrapers and an
economical and safe way to supply them with electricity has long
been a concern of the local government.
</P>
<P>
The Municipal Economic Commission decided to study the use of
such a system in the mid-1980s and the first pilot system was set
up in 1995 in the Central Hospital of Huangpu District. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's Volcano Erupted Three Times in a Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's Popocatepetl
volcano erupted three times on Monday, causing no deaths or
injuries, according to the National Disaster Prevention Center.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the volcano, about 80 kilometers east of
the capital City, spewed burning lava and a column of ash more
than four kilometers high.
</P>
<P>
The National Disaster Prevention Center warned local residents
to keep at least seven kilometers away from the crater, where
tremors are still reported.
</P>
<P>
The authorities said that the tremors triggered by the volcano
eruptions were felt in the municipalities of Atlixco and
Amecameca, located within 20 kilometers away from the volcano.
</P>
<P>
Over 100,000 people live 15 kilometers away from the
5,230-meter high volcano, and one million people 35 kilometers
away. Last week the volcano registered its largest eruption in
four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
