<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Porcelain Capital Developing Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Jingdezhen, known as China's
porcelain capital in eastern Jiangxi Province, will use its
historic and natural resources to develop tourism in the coming
century.
</P>
<P>
A number of old villages, roads, virgin forests, and valuable
historic relics, including 30 old porcelain kilns, two
1,000-year-old brick pagodas, and 136 buildings that are about 500
years old, have been discovered in the city.
</P>
<P>
Jingdezhen has a history of porcelain making that goes back to
the Five Dynasties period (907-979 A.D.). The name "Jingde" comes from
an emperor's reign title in the year 1004 of the Song Dynasty
(960-1279). It is the only city in China named for a reign title.
</P>
<P>
With its advanced porcelain-making techniques and important
place as a communications link between Jiangxi, Anhui and Zhejiang
provinces, Jingdezhen has been a center for porcelain, handcrafts,
and agricultural products since the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
