<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South American Presidents to Sign Extradition Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of six
South American countries will sign two extradition treaties on
Thursday valid for the whole region, a Brazilian diplomat said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Negotiators from South Common Market (Mercosur) countries and
two Mercosur associate members, Chile and Bolivia, approved
extradition between Mercosur members and associate members on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two pacts reached between the four Mercosur countries --
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay -- have to be ratified by
the Mercosur council, which is made up of the finance and foreign
ministers of the four countries, before being signed by their
presidents.
</P>
<P>
The justice ministers of the six countries set the norms for
the treaties during a meeting in Brasilia last month.
</P>
<P>
The pacts, however, do not include the extradition of political
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The agreements are expected to speed up extradition of drug
traffickers and terrorists between Mercosur countries and their
partners, officials said.
</P>
<P>
But the pacts do not allow Brazil to request the extradition of
its citizens committing crimes in other countries due to a
constitutional ban on such a practice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
