<HEADLINE> Indonesia May Quit OPEC Membership, Says Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia signaled it might
quit as member of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC), citing the organization's failure to stabilize
the world oil prices, Antara News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"After we make considerations, Indonesia has decided it may
quit OPEC," Rachmat Sudibyo, member of the Mines and Energy
Minister's expert staff said.
</P>
<P>
Many parties had previously pressed the government to abandon
its OPEC membership on the grounds that the organization failed to
control the world crude price which now slumped to 9.8 U.S.
dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Oil observer Bahrawi Sanusi said the crude price's slump, the
first since the OPEC meeting in Vienna, Austria, on November 25,
indicated that the organization did not serve its members'
interest.
</P>
<P>
The organization lacked discipline in controlling oil prices,
he said, adding that almost all the 11 OPEC members had violated
their quotas but none of them were subjected to sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Sudibyo said, however, Indonesia needed to think of the bad
impact of its wish to abandon its OPEC membership.
</P>
<P>
"This (the wish) will eventually give an impression that OPEC
is powerless," he told reporters on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia did not want that to happen.
</P>
<P>
As an OPEC member, he said, Indonesia would keep on discussing
with other OPEC members the proper quota of each OPEC member.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
