<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiyuan Catalogs Ancient Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Taiyuan, capital of Shanxi
Province in north China, has introduced cataloging to protect 232
ancient trees.
</P>
<P>
Taiyuan has 29 varieties of ancient trees surviving in temple
complexes, as well as at historical sites and locations throughout
the urban area. The oldest tree has thrived for more than 1,300
years.
</P>
<P>
Individual identification cards carry pertinent information,
including the species, age, class of protection and responsible
unit.
</P>
<P>
These varieties include Chinese scholartrees, oriental
arborvitae, Chinese pine, ginkgo, cedar and magnolia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
