<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, December 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Officials of the United States and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) on Monday met at the State
Department in Washington for their third session in four days.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley said the U.S. team was
led by U.S. Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Charles Kartman
while the head of the DPRK team was vice Foreign Minister Kim
Kye-Gwan. (US-DPRK-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- NASA' scientists said that the first close-up
images of Mars's north pole taken by the Mars Global Surveyor
suggests there is a thick ice cap there, but it is only half the
size of the ice cap covering Greenland and only 4 percent of the
Antarctica's entile ice sheets.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the American Geophysical Union meeting in San
Francisco on Sunday, they said that the ice cap measures 750 miles
and is 1.8 miles thick. (US-Mars-Ice Cap)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- At least five people were killed in a plane crash
Monday in Canada's French-speaking province of Quebec.
</P>
<P>
Three people have been rescued from the freezing waters and
five people confirmed to be dead, reports said.
(Canada-Plane-Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. weapons inspectors were to start
surprise visits to Iraq's suspected sites to test Iraq's promise
of resuming full cooperation with the United Nations, chief
U.N. weapons inspector Richard Butler said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after meeting with the president of the
Security Council Monday morning, Butler said, "We are about to
begin visits to sites where we have, under our mandate, a reason
to go from the point of view of prohibited weapons programs."
(UNSCOM-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli legislators postponed a vote on a bill
calling for early elections Monday night, after Prime Minister
Benjamin Natanyahu engineered a motion of non-confidence in his
own government.
</P>
<P>
By engineering the no-confidence motion, the prime minister has
gained at least one week during which he can try his best to
persuade his hard-line coalition partners not to act against the
government. (Israel-Parliament)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States on Monday insisted a pullback
on the West bank by Israel must proceed on time while Israel said
it was difficult to continue the peace process because of
Palestinian street violence in recent days.
</P>
<P>
At a joint news conference with Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel
Sharon, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the United
States "wants to see the process moving forward." (US-Mideast-Wye
Agreement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South Africa Monday withdrew more troops from
Lesotho after a September military intervention in the neighboring
kingdom, a senior officer said in Maseru, the capital of Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
About 200 South African National Defense Force (SANDF) troops
left Maseru in the morning for Bleomfontein, a central city about
150 km west from Lesotho border, said Colonel Hannes van der
Merwe, commander of the combined South African and Botswana
troops. (SAfrica-Lesotho-Troops Pullout)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- President Laurent Kabila of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) is expecting to end the civil war in his
country by Christmas, Southern African Broadcasting Association
(SABA) reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka based SABA quoted Kabila as saying that a cease-fire
was possible. He made the comments during a surprise meeting with
Namibian President Sam Nujoma, a key ally in his four-month
struggle against rebels backed by Rwanda and Uganda.
(SAfrica-Kabila-Civil War) 
</P>
</TEXT>
