<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0362 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wembley Stadium Twin Towers 'Have to Go' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Senior figures at Wembley
stadium admitted Monday that they will have to demolish the twin
towers when the stadium is redeveloped.
</P>
<P>
The world-famous landmarks appeared to have won a reprieve
last month after news of their demise was released, but now it
seems that only replicas will survive.
</P>
<P>
The latest admission is likely to anger Brent Council, which
gave redevelopment the go-ahead on the basis of the towers'
survival.
</P>
<P>
The local authority has warned that planning permission could
be taken away if the 75-year-old towers were to be removed in the
300m scheme.
</P>
<P>
Wembley Stadium vice-chairman Jarvis Astaire told a sports
forum on Monday: "The towers will have to go because the entire
stadium will need widening. But I believe replicas will be built."
</P>
<P>
Work on rebuilding the stadium has already been delayed from
its original start date of next May and is now not expected to
begin before next autumn.
</P>
<P>
A Celine Dion concert is being held there next summer and
England are hoping to stage their European Championship qualifier
against Luxembourg at Wembley on 4 September 1999 before the
bulldozers move in.
</P>
<P>
Fears for the towers were first raised following comments by
Football Association chief executive Graham Kelly.
</P>
<P>
He said he was uncertain if they would be "significant" to a
new 88,000-seat arena, forming the centrepiece of a bid to bring
the World Cup to England in 2006.
</P>
<P>
One option is to move the grade II listed towers to form a
gateway to the new national stadium.
</P>
<P>
But not only would that prove expensive, there is also no
guarantee they can be successfully relocated.
</P>
<P>
No decision on the future of the 126ft high towers can be
taken until Wembley becomes the property of English National
Stadium Trust, which is buying it from Wembley Plc for 103
million pounds.
</P>
<P>
With 120m having been granted by the English Sports Council,
that leaves 17m to be used during the design phase.
</P>
<P>
The FA aims to raise 200m towards the development costs
through the City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0363 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Players to Play Exhibition in Atlantic City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- With the lockout showing no
signs of ending, idle NBA stars will take part in a charity game
December 19 in Atlantic City, New Jersey, but the participants
will not inlude Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Plans for the contest, which will feature at least 16 players
who have represented the United States in international
competition, were announced today by agents David Falk and Arn
Tellem along with Showtime, which will televise the contest from
the Atlantic City Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, however, will not be in uniform. Curtis Polk,
president of Falk Associates Management Enterprises, which
represents Jordan, said the Chicago Bulls guard did not want to
send a "mixed message" to fans since he has not decided whether
to return this season.
</P>
<P>
Players Association president Patrick Ewing will be among the
players and will be joined by Karl Malone, Penny Hardaway, Tim
Hardaway, Allan Houston, Reggie Miller, Gary Payton, Dominique
Wilkins, Vin Baker, Glen Rice, Alonzo Mourning, Tom Gugliotta and
Mitch Richmond. The rest of the participants will be announced at
a later date.
</P>
<P>
Portions of the proceeds for the game will be donated to
UNICEF and the rest will benefit the "bottom tier" of NBA players
most affected by the lockout, which is in its 159th day. Today's
news conference was also used as a vehicle to blame the NBA
owners for the work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
"This is a tremendous opportunity to show how much the players
want to be on court," said Falk. "There has been confusion of
intention. Players want to be on the court. Unfortunately, the
lockout has prevented that. It gives the chance to say thanks to
the fans. It is a chance to show love for the game."
</P>
<P>
Most of the tickets will range between $25 and $50 with some
courtside seats selling for $1,000. The players will not be paid
and organizers predicted the game will generate revenue in "the
low seven figures."
</P>
<P>
"Our livelihoods are at stake. We have families and our
competitive juices are flowing," added Mourning. "Right now we
are being neglected and it's an unfortunate situation. That's why
were are playing these games."
</P>
<P>
NBA owners and the union met for 10 1/2 hours on Thursday in
New York but reported little progress toward ending the lockout.
NBA commissioner David Stern on Thursday publicly acknowleged the
possibility of canceling the entire season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0364 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
