<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEMA Group to Replace IBM to Be IOC World-wide Sponsor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) has appointed SEMA Group, a leading global
Information Technology (IT) company, to become a partner in the
IOC world-wide sponsor program.
</P>
<P>
The contract will be signed on the occasion of the IOC
Executive Board on December 12, 1998 between IOC President Juan
Antonio Samaranch and SEMA Group Chief Executive Officer Pierre
Bonelli, said the IOC in a press release received here today.
</P>
<P>
"This agreement represents the largest sports-related
information technology contract ever awarded," said the IOC.
</P>
<P>
As of January 1, 2001, the SEMA Group will provide services in
the areas of systems integration, operations management and
applications delivery for the Olympic Movement from 2001-2008,
encompassing the 2004 and 2008 Olympic Games and the 2002 and
2006 Olympic Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
The IOC said that the current IT partner, IBM, will continue
to provide all support and services through the Sydney 2000
Olympic Games. IBM has been a IOC partner since 1993 and has
played a key role in providing state-of-the-art IT for Olympic
Games Organizing Committees.
</P>
<P>
SEMA Group is a leading European-based systems integration
company, with extensive experience and proven skills in event
management, having provided successful IT systems to the 1992
Barcelona Olympic Games and other major sporting events,
according to the IOC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981208.0366 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
