<HEADLINE> Southeastern China Looking at Emerging Markets in EU, Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Altogether 11 countries in
Europe and Africa are emerging as markets for Fujian province in
east China.
</P>
<P>
Cao Degan, Fujian's Vice-governor in charge of foreign trade
and economic cooperation, told a recent seminar on the Asian
financial crisis that the euro and the growing African economy
could stimulate the province's exports and help Fujian get a
greater market share in the two regions.
</P>
<P>
Cao said that Fujian could save money and time in various
European countries because of the removal of currency barriers and
Fujian's products could be exported to a port of any country in
the zone, then sold to other countries by retail.
</P>
<P>
Fujian exported 9.98 billion U.S. dollars worth of goods in the
January-October period, up 3.47 percent on a year-on-year basis,
with exports to Europe increasing 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sources disclosed that foreign trade companies of Fujian will
focus on France and Germany next year.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's Africa exports still account for little of its
total. However, its medium- and low-priced products, which are the
major part in its exports, fit some African needs, according to
Chen Zuwu, director of the provincial foreign trade committee.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade contributes a great deal to Fujian's
economy. Last year, its exports totaled 11.5 billion U.S. dollars
worth, ranking fourth in China. However, its foreign trade
suffered from the Asian financial crisis and the devaluation of
currencies in some Asian countries, where 70 percent of its
exports were going.  
</P>
</TEXT>
