<HEADLINE> U.S., DPRK Hold Talks in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Officials of the United
States and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) on
Monday met at the State Department in Washington for their third
session in four days.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley said the U.S. team was
led by U.S. Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Charles Kartman
while the head of the DPRK team was vice Foreign Minister Kim
Kye-Gwan.
</P>
<P>
"The talks are being conducted in a serious atmosphere. My
understanding is that they could continue tomorrow," Foley told
a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and DPRK negotiators met in New York last Friday and
Saturday with the agenda restricted to the U.S. demand that DPRK
allow inspection of the site at the village of Kumchang-ri,
where the United States alleged there was an underground building
site which could be connected with a revived nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK has denied that the building work was
nuclear-related and has asked the United States to promise
compensation if a search proved negative.
</P>
<P>
The talks coincided with a trip to Asia by President Bill
Clinton's newly appointed coordinator of policy toward the DPRK,
former Defense secretary William Perry. 
</P>
