<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumers Borrow Strongly in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua)-- Consumers borrowing in this
country recorded a fastest increase in October since July 1996,
the Federal Reserve reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Credit outstanding grew at a 9 percent annual rate to a
seasonally adjusted 1.29 trillion U.S. dollars, according to the
U.S. central bank, which is up from rates of 4.9 percent in
September and 3.9 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
The borrowing also helps explain why the U.S. personal savings
rate went negative for the second consecutive month _ for the
first time on record. The personal savings rate is savings as a
percentage of after-tax income. Another factor is that, in
addition to borrowing more, consumers are spending part of their
stock-market gains.
</P>
<P>
The report fit with separate data showing retail sales shot up
1 percent in October, the strongest in five months. Last month,
however, major retail chains said unseasonably warm weather in the
East has hurt sales of winter clothing.
</P>
<P>
Growth in consumer credit in October was led by a catchall
category that includes loans for education, vacations, mobile
homes and boats. It shot up at a 19 percent rate, the most in
three months.
</P>
<P>
Revolving credit, primarily credit-cards, advanced at an 8
percent rate, the fastest in four months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
