<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Inspectors to Start Surprise Visits to Iraq's Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 7 (Xinhua) -- U.N. weapons inspectors
were to start surprise visits to Iraq's suspected sites to test
Iraq's promise of resuming full cooperation with the United
Nations, chief U.N. weapons inspector Richard Butler said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press after meeting with the president of the
Security Council Monday morning, Butler said, "We are about to
begin visits to sites where we have, under our mandate, a reason
to go from the point of view of prohibited weapons programs."
</P>
<P>
Butler, executive chairman of the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction, said that after those visits were finished,
either at the end of this week or early next week, he would be
able to submit a report to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on
whether Iraq had kept its promise of full cooperation or not.
</P>
<P>
Butler said that since Iraq's restoration of cooperation with
U.N. weapons inspectors on November 14, he had renewed work in
four areas, namely access to document, monitoring, interviews and
visits to so-called "capable sites" which might have a potential
for use for forbidden purposes.
</P>
<P>
The executive chairman said the fifth area, where the work was
about to start, was investigation of sites where prohibited
weapons programs might exist.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council will not start to conduct
the comprehensive review of Iraq's compliance with U.N.
resolutions until the secretary-general proves that Iraq has
cooperated fully and unconditionally with the U.N. weapons
inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
