<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Kosovo Negotiations Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States pledged
Monday to keep pushing for a political settlement in troubled
Kosovo despite the refusal by the ethnic Albanians of a U.S.
proposal for the Serbian province's future.
</P>
<P>
U.S. envoy Christopher Hill met with Deputy Director James
Steinberg of the National Security Council and Richard Holbrooke,
the chief U.S. mediator for the Balkans, at the White House to
discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
Following their meeting, David Leavy, a spokesman for the
National Security Council, said Hill would keep working on a
process designed to assure peace and stability in Kosovo and a
return to the kind of autonomy the province had until Belgrade
canceled it a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
Fehmi Agani, head of the Kosovo Albanian negotiating team, said
in Pristina that the latest version of the U.S. peace plan was
"almost identical to the Serbian proposal for Kosovo" and "cannot
be considered a basis for... future negotiations."
</P>
<P>
Leavy said the administration was continuing to make progress
in implementing U.N. resolutions designed to help civilians.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen a ceasefire, and people by and large are
returning to their homes," Leavy said. "We are determined to push
for a political settlement that will bring autonomy to Kosovo."
</P>
</TEXT>
