<HEADLINE> Egypt, Mozambique Discuss Situation in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa held talks Monday with his Mozambican counterpart Leonardo
Simao on issues in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The talks focused on the current conditions in the Democratic
Republic of Congo, the Horn of Africa and issues in some other
African countries, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mediated by the Secretary General of the United Nations Kofi
Annan, leaders of Rwanda, Uganda and DRCongo reached on November
28 a ceasefire agreement to end the fighting between rebels and
forces loyal to Congolese President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
As for the Horn of Africa, Sudan, Ethiopia, Eritrea and
Djibouti have disputes over territory and some other issues, which
are far from resolved.
</P>
<P>
Simao arrived here Sunday for a three-day visit, during which
he is expected to deliver a message to Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak from his Mozambican counterpart Joaquim Chissano on
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Moussa briefed Simao on the latest
developments of the Middle East peace process, especially on the
Palestinian-Israeli track after the signing of the Wye peace deal,
the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel signed the agreement on October 23
in Washington on Israeli withdrawal from another 13 percent of the
West Bank in exchange for Palestinians' tough crackdown on
anti-Israeli violence.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East News Agency said that Moussa and Simao will
hold talks on bilateral relations on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two officials will also co-chair the first session of the
Egyptian-Mozambican Joint Higher Committee, during which two
agreements on protecting and encouraging investments and technical
cooperation will be signed, the news agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
