<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House to Call 14 Witnesses in Two-Day Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The White House will call 14
witnesses and use two lawyers to present its defense of U.S.
President Bill Clinton during two 15-hour days Tuesday and
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The presentation will challenge the impeachment evidence
without attacking the prosecutor who gathered it, officials here
said.
</P>
<P>
The White House sent a letter informing the House of
Representatives Judiciary Committee that presidential lawyer Greg
Craig will open the presentation Tuesday and "describe briefly and
generally the president's legal and factual defense" followed by
three panels of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff will make closing
arguments Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The White House also disclosed that one of its witnesses, Yale
law professor Bruce Ackerman, will argue that any impeachment
article approved by the House this year would not be valid when
the new Congress convenes January 6.
</P>
<P>
Among the witnesses are three former members of the House
Judiciary Committee that voted to impeach President Nixon a
quarter-century ago: the Reverend Robert Drinan, a Roman Catholic
priest and former Massachusetts Democrat; Elizabeth Holtzman,
and Wayne Owens, both Democrats.
</P>
<P>
The panel was carefully chosen by presidential aides hoping to
use former lawmakers to lobby current committee members that
impeachment is too severe a penalty for Clinton's transgressions
in the Monica Lewinsky affair, and that there isn't evidence that
Clinton abused his presidential powers.
</P>
<P>
The Judiciary Committee's inquiry enters a final, crucial phase
this week with two days of presentations from White House
witnesses and attorneys beginning Tuesday. The White House asked
for four days but grudgingly accepted half that time. The
committee will consider articles of impeachment later in the week.
</P>
<P>
The committee originally gave the White House one day to rebut
charges against Clinton in the Lewinsky affair. Clinton's lawyers
last week said they wanted three or four days.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the panel's Republican and Democratic chief
counsels are expected to make closing arguments and the committee,
from late Thursday into Friday, plans to consider articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
It appears almost certain that the Judiciary Committee, split
down party lines, will send to the full House at least one article
of impeachment charging Clinton with perjury in his denials of a
sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky. Republican committee
members said they are also pushing for articles charging
obstruction of justice and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
The House then would take up impeachment the following week.
Lawmakers on both sides said a House vote is too close to call.
</P>
<P>
Even if the House votes for impeachment, it is highly unlikely
at this point that a two-thirds majority in the Senate would vote
to convict and remove Clinton from office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
