<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
MAMAMAH -- Bahraini cabinet Sunday approved a plan to privatize
transport services and authorized the Ministry of Transport and
the Ministry of Finance and Economy to take necessary measures.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs Mohammed Al-Muttawa said
that the government will continue to subsidize the power and water
sectors to benefit the consumers, the Arabic Al-Hayat reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- Oman has signed a contract with India to provide it
with 1.2 million tonnes of liquefied gas annually.
</P>
<P>
The contract will earn Oman 24 billion U.S. dollars a year,
Al-Hayat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for India to import gas from Oman.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudanese Finance Minister Abdel-Wahab Osman has
submitted a draft budget to the parliament, setting the
expenditure at 250.8 billion Sudanese pounds (1.3 billion
U.S. dollars) and the deficit at 31 billion pounds (158 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The draft also suggests a 27 percent rise in salary instead of
the 100 percent called for by the trade unions, Al-Hayat reported
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
