<HEADLINE> U.S., Israel Disagree on Carrying out Wye Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 7 (Xinhua) --The United States on Monday
insisted a pullback on the West bank by Israel must proceed on
time while Israel said it was difficult to continue the peace
process because of Palestinian street violence in recent days.
</P>
<P>
at a joint news conference with Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel
Sharon, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the United
States "wants to see the process moving forward."
</P>
<P>
"It is very important, we have made very clear, that both sides
need to fulfil their obligations and it"s very important to create
an environment that will allow the Wye agreement to go forward,"
Albright to the news conference.
</P>
<P>
"There is a timetable that was established. I spoke to Chairman
(Yasser) Arafat about the necessity of living up to security
obligations and I have spoken to the foreign minister about the
importance of the Israeli side fulfilling its obligations.
</P>
<P>
"We think that Wye is very carefully written and we want to see
both sides carry out what they need to do," she added.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu signed the
Wye agreement at the White House on Oct. 23 after nine days of
intensive U.S. mediation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement offers the Palestinians a further 13 percent of
the West Bank in returning for security measures for Israel.
</P>
<P>
At the joint news conference, Sharon accused the Palestinians
of breaking the Wye agreement, indicating the Palestinian
Authority had not taken security measures.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the recent clashes between Israeli soldiers
and Palestinians against a background of Palestinians demand that
Israel set free more political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Israel released the first 250 of promised 750 Palestinian
prisoners last month, but they were mainly criminals, not
so-called security prisoners as the Palestinians have demanded.
</P>
<P>
"If the Palestinians will not comply with the Wye agreement,
every part of it, Israel will not be able to continue, although we
would like to. We believe that every step should be taken and
everything should be done on a basis of mutual reciprocity,"
Sharon said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said President
Bill Clinton intends to go to Israel on Saturday despite
Netanyahu's lack of enthusiasm for the visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
