<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vote on Early Elections Bill Put Off in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 7 (Xinhua)-- Israeli legislators postponed
a vote on a bill calling for early elections Monday night, after
Prime Minister Benjamin Natanyahu engineered a motion of
non-confidence in his own government.
</P>
<P>
By engineering the no-confidence motion, the prime minister has
gained at least one week during which he can try his best to
persuade his hard-line coalition partners not to act against the
government.
</P>
<P>
The motion enabled Netanyahu to avoid an immediate humiliation
which would have been caused by the passage of the bill at its
first reading, Israel Raido reported.
</P>
<P>
But the prime minister is also confronted with the danger that
his government will collapse immediately if the no-confidence
motion is approved.
</P>
<P>
The bill seemed likely to be passed by a majority due to the
support of some coalition Knesset (Parliament) members, who
opposed the recent land-for-peace deal which Netanyahu signed with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in Washington in October.
</P>
<P>
The bill calls for the dissolution of the Knesset and thus
early elections. Sponsored by the Labor party, it needs a
majority of at least 61 votes in all its three readings before it
becomes law.
</P>
<P>
"I don't wish (early) elections," Netanyahu said to reporters
as he was busy talking with his coalition members in the
Knesset before the bill was scheduled to be presented for a
vote.
</P>
<P>
"But if the majority of the Knesset members don't support
the policy (of the government), that's their choice," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to members of the Labor-led opposition, those
who sided against Netanyahu included at least four members of
his coalition, including Agriculture Minister Rafael Eitan.
</P>
<P>
The bill passed its preliminary reading in late July, just
one day before the Knesset went for a long summer recess.
But that reading needed only a simple majority to be passed.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, the bill was originally presented as a protest
over Netanyahu's foot-dragging on the Middle East peace process,
but it is now supported by some of his coalition members because
he has signed a peace deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
